<FIRST>r a AM-HeathertonTrial     06-24 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heatherton Trial,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury: Joey Heatherton Did Not Assault Clerk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury ruled Friday that Joey Heatherton was
negligent but did not assault or beat a passport clerk who claimed
the entertainer attacked her in 1985, and both women said they were
pleased with the verdict.
   The jury refused to award any money for pain and suffering,
emotional distress or punitive damages, but it assessed Miss
Heatherton $20,500 for the year's salary the clerk lost and her
medical bills.
   Mary Polik sued Miss Heatherton, 44, for $6 million, claiming
that the entertainer ripped out her hair, slapped her and ``banged
and bashed'' her head on a counter top after she told her she had
the wrong photos for a passport and that she needed the $35 fee in
exact change.
   ``I'm very happy,'' Heatherton said. ``I've been vindicated and
I'm glad the situation has been resolved.''
   ``Ms. Polik was looking for a $6 million gold mine and instead
she's back to where she was in 1985 _ working for a living like
everybody else,'' added Heatherton's attorney, William Kunstler.
   Polik also said she was pleased with the verdict. ``No human
being has the right to beat up on another,'' she said.
   Polik's lawyer, Marie Ng, said she considered the verdict a
victory for Polik. ``I am thrilled,'' she said. ``The jury found Ms.
Heatherton negligent. They said that intentionally or
unintentionally she did what she was accused of and ordered her to
pay for medical expenses and loss of earnings.''
   Polik, 27, said she suffered pinched neck nerves, headaches,
dizziness and nausea following the July 8, 1985, attack.
</TEXT>
