<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--DisgruntledCustomer     06-24 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Disgruntled Customer,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Crashed Through Dealership Doors, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENSHAW, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disgruntled customer has been accused of
staging a one-man demolition derby at a suburban Pittsburgh car
dealership.
   Police said Albert H. ``Pete'' Ruff, 72, drove a 1989 Toyota
through the glass doors of Krebs Toyota's showroom in Shaler
Township on June 15 and crashed into five vehicles, including a
police cruiser called to the scene.
   He caused about $5,000 damage, authorities said.
   The dispute was related to a car Ruff had leased from Krebs,
according to Mary Kay Condie, District Justice James Bowen's
secretary.
   ``He apparently found out that he could have got a better deal by
buying the car,'' she said after the retiree's arraignment Wednesday.
   Ruff has been charged with reckless endangerment, criminal
mischief, simple assault, terroristic threats and resisting arrest.
The criminal complaint against Ruff alleges he threatened dealership
salesmen ``with bodily harm.''
</TEXT>
