<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ChildCare Bjt   06-24 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Child Care Bill; Fight Shifts To House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate passage of an unprecedented child-care
package sends the debate to the House, where Republicans and the
Bush administration promise to fight anew for a plan without the
billion-dollar subsidies being pushed by Democrats.
   ``We've made a significant step toward providing affordable, safe
care for American children and equal economic opportunity for
American women,'' Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
said Friday just before the measure passed on a voice vote.
   With $1.75 billion in direct subsidies for the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1 and more than $2 billion a year in tax credits, the
Senate package represents the greatest government effort ever to
address child-care needs of working parents and its first major
effort since an emergency plan adopted during World War II.
   Action on child care is expected to accelerate in the House next
week, and Republicans vowed to fight for legislation far different
from the Senate's plan.
   ``This is just a first step and a very short step,'' said Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``I'm going to encourage the
administration not to view what happened in the Senate as final.''
   With the White House raising the possibility of a veto, Democrats
too said they hoped to strike a compromise, although they are not
willing to abandon the subsidy approach.
   ``We are quite willing to hear the administration, to listen to
their suggestions and their recommendations,'' said Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass.
   It appeared early Friday that partisan bickering would threaten a
two-week Senate recess. But Republicans, after losing several
attempts to significantly change the Democratic bill, relented and
struck a deal with majority Democrats on a timetable to end the
debate.
   Only a handful of senators remained when the measure passed. The
leadership had agreed to the voice vote so those lawmakers who had
to catch flights out of Washington would not be recorded as absent
for the vote.
   Democrats characterized the legislation as historic and a
long-overdue effort to support low-income parents who must work but
cannot find affordable child care.
   ``The real winners, the children, are closer to a safer, more
effective and affordable child-care program,'' said Kennedy.
   The measure was the product of an unusual alliance between
liberal Democrat Christopher Dodd of Connecticut and Utah Republican
Orrin Hatch, whose conservative credentials helped Democrats brush
aside many Republican attacks on the plan.
   ``This is a monumental achievement,'' Hatch said.
   Despite changes designed to accommodate Bush, Dole said the
measure contained ``nothing for the president of the United States.''
   Bush spokesman Marlin Fitzwater added that despite the addition
of provisions Bush favored, the bill remained ``a candidate for a
veto.''
   In addition to the $1.75 billion authorization for child-care
subsidies, the measure includes three tax-relief provisions designed
to help low- and moderate-income families pay for child care and
health insurance for their children.
   One would supplement the existing Earned Income Tax Credit to
provide up to $750 more for parents whose annual incomes are less
than $10,000 and have two or more children under age 5. Parents
could receive a $500 credit for one eligible child.
   The second tax-related provision allows those who qualify for the
existing Dependent Care Tax Credit to get 90 percent of their credit
up front, a move designed to give cash to families who are eligible
for the credit but cannot take advantage of it because they don't
make enough to owe federal taxes.
   The third provision, which Republicans vigorously opposed, would
provide parents with annual incomes of less than $12,000 with a tax
credit of to $500 to pay 50 percent of the cost of buying health
insurance for their children.
</TEXT>
