<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HUD-Charities     06-24 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Charities,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top HUD Officials Solicited Donations From Those They Regulated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two top officials in the New York regional office
of the Department of Housing and Urban Development regularly
solicited charitable donations from the people they regulated, The
New York Times reported in its Saturday editions.
   Some of the builders, housing managers, architects, lawyers and
local housing authority directors approached by Joseph D.
Monticciolo, the previous New York HUD administrator, and Geraldine
McGann, the current one, told the Times they felt that agreeing to
requests to buy tickets or make donations would improve their
chances when it came to securing HUD financing.
   ``Does it help you? I'd say yes,'' said Joseph Barry, a builder
in Hoboken, N.J., with several HUD projects who has given generously.
   ``It's perceived as the cost of doing business with HUD in the
current political climate,'' said Robert McKay, director of the
Council of Large Public Housing Authorities.
   It is a violation of the federal ethics code to use ``public
office or official title for private gain,'' even if the money goes
to charity, according to Mary Brunette, a spokeswoman for HUD
Secretary Jack F. Kemp.
   No one has suggested that the money raised at the charity
testimonials was misused.
   But Brunette said, ``HUD employees should not use their positions
to solicit contributions, even for a charity, from the business and
governmental community that they're working with.'' Violations can
result in dismissal.
   Monticciolo, who ran the department's office that includes New
York, New Jersey, Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands from 1981 to
1988, and Mrs. McGann, the administrator since June 1988, did not
respond to telephone messages left at their homes, the Times said.
</TEXT>
