<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-37CentRailway     06-24 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-37 Cent Railway,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreigners Inquire about Sale of Railway for 37 Cents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Malayan Railway is correct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inquiries about the sale of the
Malayan Railway for 37 cents continue to pour in from abroad, the
transport ministry said today.
   The minister, Ling Liong Sik, told reporters no decision has been
made on a buyer of the railway because the government Economic
Planning Unit was still evaluating recommendations by Bumiputra
Merchant Bank on the privatization of the railway. There are no
private railways in Malaysia.
   Officials said Japanese, Canadians and Americans were among those
who were serious about buying the railway, which has about 1,000
miles of track and hundreds of millions of dollars worth of assets,
including its rolling stock, land, buildings and trucks. It also has
debts of about $407 million.
   Eighteen months ago, the government announced it planned to sell
the Malayan Railway for one ringgit, or 37 cents, as part of plans
to privatize many state companies, including Malaysia Airlines, the
Telecommuncations Department, ports and the National Electricity
board.
</TEXT>
