<FIRST>r w PM-CrashTests     06-24 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash Tests,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>NHTSA Releases New Crash-Test Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal engineers say crash tests of 19 cars
show drivers of the Chevrolet Astro Van have the greatest chance of
head injury in an accident.
   The van's manufacturer, General Motors Corp., said the federal
tests aren't a valid indicator of crash-worthiness.
   The Astro Van was among 12 vehicles listed in the third round of
crash-test results released Friday by the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration. The vehicles were tested under NHTSA's
program to provide consumers a guide to the safety of 1989 vehicles.
   Results of seven other vehicles had been released previously.
   GM said the federal test results ``do not reflect the actual
safety performance of these vehicles on the road'' because the test
is done on only one vehicle.
   The vehicles were smashed at 35 mph into a fixed barrier, and the
stresses that resulted were measured by sensors on human-shaped
dummies protected by seat belts or other crash-protection devices.
   NHTSA engineers reported stresses on the head as an index called
the head injury criterion. The higher the index, the greater the
likelihood of injury.
   The Astro Van crash test produced a head injury criterion of
1,849 for the driver-side dummy in the Astro Van, NHTSA said. The
figure was more than double the head injury criterion recorded in a
test of the Mitsubishi van, the only other van tested this year.
   The Mitsubishi had a head injury criterion of 805, NHTSA said.
   Federal regulations require cars on the market to produce a head
injury criterion no greater than 1,000 in tests conducted by the
automakers. The public tests done by NHTSA and the mandatory tests
to meet safety regulations are not considered comparable because the
automakers' tests are done at 30 mph.
   Other new test results by weight class produced these driver head
injury criteria:
   _Subcompact cars: Mercury Tracer 4-door hatchback, 940.
   _Compact cars: Ford Probe 2-door hatchback, 970.
   _Large and mid-size cars: Chevrolet Caprice 4-door sedan, 1,328;
Chrysler Fifth Avenue 4-door sedan, 786; Eagle Premier 4-door sedan,
877; Lincoln Continental 4-door sedan, 863; and Plymouth Acclaim
4-door sedan, 663.
   _Trucks, vans and multi-purpose vehicles: Chevrolet S-10 Blazer,
834; Ford Bronco II, 994; and Jeep Cherokee, 968.
   NHTSA said small differences in test results aren't considered
significant.
   Previously released test results, by weight class, were:
   _Subcompact: Dodge Daytona 2-door hatchback, 399; Honda Civic CRX
2-door hatchback, 750; Mitsubishi Mirage 4-door sedan, 960.
   _Compact: Mitsubishi Galant 4-door sedan, 971.
   _Large and mid-size: Dodge Spirit 4-door sedan, 1,421; Eagle
Medallion 4-door sedan, 745; Ford Thunderbird 2-door, 541.
</TEXT>
