<FIRST>r w PM-US-China     06-24 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Asks `Patience, Forbearance' on China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional leaders are pressing President
Bush for tough action against China but the White House is appealing
for patience, saying it will be a long time before Washington and
Beijing return to normal relations.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush, in a
meeting with senators Friday, asked for ``their understanding that
he was trying to do the best job possible to express the concerns of
the United States government, the outrage of American people in
terms of what they had seen there, and at the same time, to preserve
our relations as best we could.''
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del, said Bush ``asked for our patience and
forbearance.''
   Chinese authorities this week executed 27 people charged with
taking part in pro-democracy demonstrations.
   On Capitol Hill, calls continued for a stronger White House
response. Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said: ``I believe the
president must take tough action and block trade with and new
investments in China right now.'' He added that ``there are some
values which take precedence over commerce.''
   ``The stark barbarism of the communist regime is unforgivable to
all civilized people,'' Byrd said.
   ``The dust has settled on the blood of peaceful demonstrators,
and the regime wantonly spills fresh blood on top of old. It
executes its young on the altar of old men's egos and fears. America
cannot possibly be in the position of rewarding, appearing to
reward, or in any way countenance these acts,'' Byrd added.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, who has called
on Bush to be more forceful in denouncing the Chinese government's
actions, attended the White House meeting but did not speak to
reporters afterwards.
   At the White House, Biden said Bush did not suggest lawmakers
should mute their criticism of his policy, and ``he made it very
clear that he believed that it was appalling what was happening in
China in terms of human rights.''
   He quoted Bush as saying ``there was a long road that was going
to have to be traveled in that relationship and that we shouldn't
move precipitously.''
   Fitzwater said Bush, in referring to ``a long road,'' was talking
about ``the events that have taken place there, and the amount of
time that anyone can foresee before we would have a return to a
normalcy or anything like we had before.''
   Unlike some of his congressional colleagues, Biden withheld
criticism or suggestions about Bush's policy.
   `I don't believe that we should suggest to the president
precisely what he should do,'' Biden said. ``I think what we should
do is make it clear to the president and make it clear to the
Chinese that there isn't any option that is beyond consideration.''
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said, ``I think the president was
saying that it's very simple to take a precipitous action, break
relations with China, but the long-range interests of the United
States require delicate, appropriate, judgmental handling of the
situation.''
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said the acts of the Chinese government
against its own citizens ``must be met by an unrelenting and
unmistakable willingness to change immediately and significantly the
status quo of our relationship.''
   ``The bullets aimed at pro-democracy students, workers and
teachers are also aimed at us,'' Kerry said. ``Each shot that takes
a life, when met by silence, indifference or sense of impotence,
also takes with it a piece of who we are and what we are supposed to
stand for.''
</TEXT>
