<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Kevin Bacon, star of the movie ``She's
Having A Baby,'' has a real-life baby of his own.
   His wife had a healthy 8-pound, 5-ounce boy on Friday.
   Actress Kyra Sedgwick gave birth to Travis Sedg Bacon at 2 a.m.
at an unidentified hospital, said Bacon's spokeswoman, Heidi
Schaeffer.
   Travis is the couple's first child.
   Bacon and Miss Sedgwick were married in September 1988 after
meeting about a year earlier on the set of ``Lemon Sky,'' an
American Playhouse production on PBS.
   Besides ``She's Having A Baby,'' Bacon stars in the recently
released `Criminal Law.'' He also appeared in ``Footloose'' and will
be seen in ``The Big Picture,'' coming out in the fall.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for actor Rob Lowe will ask a federal
judge Monday to dismiss a lawsuit stemming from a sexual videotape
he allegedly made of a teen-age girl in Atlanta.
   Lena Arlene Wilson sued Lowe, contending he enticed her daughter,
Jan Parsons, then 16, into a videotaped encounter with another
woman. The incident occurred last summer, when the Brat Pack star
was in town for the Democratic National Convention.
   The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages.
   U.S. District Judge G. Ernest Tidwell scheduled a hearing Monday
on a motion by Lowe's attorneys to dismiss the lawsuit. They also
are seeking to recover court costs from Ms. Wilson and her attorney.
   A motion by Lowe's attorneys denies that he ``has committed any
wrongful acts giving rise to liability.''
   According to published reports and court documents, Miss Parsons
and a friend met Lowe, star of films including ``About Last Night''
and ``St. Elmo's Fire,'' at downtown Atlanta's Rio nightclub during
the convention last July. The reports say they returned to his hotel
suite, where they had sex with him and each other as Lowe taped the
encounter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. MORITZ, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burghers are going to the polls
this weekend to decide whether Dutch brewery tycoon Alfred H.
Heineken can tear down a 70-year-old villa surrounding his
multimillion-dollar pied-a-terre at this luxury resort.
   Results are expected Sunday.
   The yellow, 71-year-old Villa Boehler has been a thorn in
Heineken's side since he bought a hillside residence in St. Moritz
decades ago. He paid a reported $2.7 million in 1983 to buy the
villa and its grounds.
   But a storm of protest erupted when he asked local authorities to
allow him to tear down the villa and replace it with an annex to his
own place.
   Heineken has said in various interviews that the villa, built for
an Austrian industrialist by renowned German architect Heinrich
Tessenow in 1917, is a ``bunker'' and a ``revolting yellow
monstrosity.''
   Hans Rutishauser, chief curator of monuments of Grisons, the
canton that includes St. Moritz, has said the villa is ``unique and
original'' and should come under official protection.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joey Heatherton said she was ``vindicated'' by a
jury ruling that she was negligent, but did not assault or beat a
passport clerk who claimed the entertainer attacked her in 1985.
   The jury Friday assessed Miss Heatherton $20,500 for the year's
salary the clerk lost and her medical bills. The jury refused to
award any money for pain and suffering, emotional distress or
punitive damages.
   Mary Polik sued Miss Heatherton, 44, for $6 million, claiming
that the entertainer ripped out her hair, slapped her and ``banged
and bashed'' her head on a counter top after she told her she had
the wrong photos for a passport and that she needed the $35 fee in
exact change.
   ``I'm very happy,'' Heatherton said. ``I've been vindicated and
I'm glad the situation has been resolved.''
   Polik, 27, also said she was pleased with the verdict. ``No human
being has the right to beat up on another,'' she said.
   Polik said she suffered pinched neck nerves, headaches, dizziness
and nausea following the July 8, 1985, attack.
