<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-OilSpill 5thLd-Writethru a0415 06-24 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0415,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Runs Aground, Leaks Oil Into Ocean</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JO2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with federal officials arriving,
oil washing up on shore, additional quotes from DiPrete, delete outdated
material. Picks up 12th graf pvs: `Michael A. ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil tanker hit an offshore rock Friday
afternoon and leaked about 1 million gallons of heating oil into the
Atlantic Ocean, the Coast Guard said.
   The 560-foot tanker World Prodigy, carrying 7.6 million gallons
of No. 2 heating oil, struck a rock at Brenton Reef, immediately
south of Newport, at 4:40 p.m., said Petty Officer Ellen Harrington
of the Coast Guard office in Boston.
   The ship, bound for Providence, was pulled off the rock almost
immediately and anchored nearby. The leak was stopped at about 9:10
p.m., after about 1 million gallons of oil had leaked, Harrington
said.
   The Navy began replacing booms around the ship, which sails under
a Greek flag, with a containment curtain shortly after 10 p.m.
``They'll determine overnight what the immediate environmental
concerns are and place booms around those areas,'' she said.
   Like a boom, the plastic curtain is deployed around the spill,
with its bottom weighted to keep it under water and its top
suspended by buoys to contain the oil.
   Some of the oil was washing up on Castle Hill beaches early
Saturday, said Gov. Edward D. DiPrete.
   He said the ship's captain told him he had made a mistake in not
having a pilot on board and also in plotting the course.
   President Bush sent Environmental Protection Agency Administrator
William Reilly, Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan and other White
House advisers to the scene early Saturday, and they met DiPrete
shortly after midnight and planned to tour the affected area.
   Arthur Markos, DiPrete's chief of staff, said state officials are
considering legal action, but plan no criminal charges. ``Our bay is
very important to us. We're a very small state,'' he said.
   Michael A. Annarummo, deputy director of the state Department of
Environmental Management, said Coast Guard divers had reported
finding two huge holes in the ship.
   ``There's a long 150-foot knifelike gash and divers are now
talking about a wider gash lower on the ship,'' Annarummo said.
   Annarummo said state officials were confident they had enough
booms to contain the spill, and said it was a lucky that the spill
was heating oil.
   ``It's a light fuel oil,'' Annarummo said. ``The plus of that is
you don't get the heavy staining or coating or adhesion. It breaks
up easier and evaporates.''
   Harrington said the slick was moving east, parallel to the shore
and away from the mouth of Narragansett Bay, but Annarummo said
sensitive wildlife areas in the bay could be in danger by morning.
``That tide's going to change on us,'' he said.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries or harm to wildlife.
   The Coast Guard said the ship is owned by Ballard Shipping, but
did not know who owns the cargo.
   Brenton Reef, a nautical landmark where America's Cup yacht races
were held for many years, is within sight of the shore and of the
main shipping route into Narragansett Bay. The cause of the accident
was not known, she said.
   Coast Guard Lt. Alan Brown said the spill should be a lot easier
to contain than the crude oil spill that devastated Alaska's Prince
William Sound last winter when the tanker Exxon Valdez struck a rock
near the port of Valdez.
   ``With any luck at all, the seas are calm enough that we'll be
able to boom all around it,'' Brown said. ``Nothing like Alaska
where it got out of hand before anyone was there.''
   Because the site is in the populous Northeast, it will take much
less time to get booms and cleanup equipment into place, he said.
   The odor of the spilled oil wafted through this affluent resort
city. ``Boy, it's enough to knock you off your feet,'' said Rhode
Island Secretary of State Kathleen S. Connell, who lives near the
shore in suburban Middletown.
   The Alaska spill occurred March 23, when the tanker Exxon Valdez
ran aground on Bligh Reef, a well-marked navigation hazard about 25
miles south of Valdez. The 987-foot tanker had just picked up a full
load of 11.3 million gallons of oil at Valdez, the northernmost
ice-free port in the United States and the southern terminus of
Alaska pipeline.
   At one point, the tanker was spilling 20,000 gallons of oil per
hour into pristine Prince William Sound.
   Exxon later fired the tanker's captain, Joseph Hazelwood, after
tests revealed his blood alcohol level was above legal limits more
than nine hours after the accident. He faces criminal charges,
including reckless endangerment, and operating a vessel while drunk.
   Exxon later was criticized because no containment booms were put
around the tanker until more than 11 hours after the wreck.
   Bush initially rejected requests by Alaska officials to
federalize the clean-up efforts, insisting that Exxon could do the
job. But on April 7, he ordered the military to join the clean-up
effort.
</TEXT>
