<DOCNO> AP890624-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-ChildCare-AtAGlance     06-24 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Child Care-At A Glance,450</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of the child-care packaged
passed Friday by the Senate. Changes are likely when the House takes
up the bill.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>SUBSIDIES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislation authorizes $1.75 billion in federal subsidies for
child care in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, money that still
must be appropriated. Seventy percent of the money would have to be
used to help parents pay for child care. Twenty-two percent is
earmarked for state programs such as grants to and training of
child-care providers. The remaining 8 percent would be used for
states to administer the programs. States which certified that
availability of child care was more of a problem than affordability
could reduce to 65 percent the amount for parents and increase to 27
percent the amount used on state programs.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TAX CREDITS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   There are three tax breaks for low-income and moderate-income
families:
   _Child Health Credit. Parents with annual incomes of less than
$12,000 could receive a tax credit of up to $500 to help pay the
cost of health insurance for their children. Families with annual
incomes of $12,000 to $18,000 would get a smaller credit. This
credit would first be available in 1991.
   _Refundable Dependent Care Credit. Beginning in 1992, families
who now are eligible for the existing Dependent Care Tax Credit
could receive 90 percent of their credit up front through monthly
installments in their paychecks. ``Refundable'' means the measure is
designed to provide the money to families who are eligible but do
not get to take advantage of the credit currently because they do
not make enough to owe any federal income taxes against which the
credit would be applied.
   _Supplemental Earned Income Tax Credit. The existing credit would
provide families with annual incomes of less than $10,000 with a
$500 credit for a child under the age of 5 and a $750 credit if they
have two or more eligible children. The credit, available beginning
in 1991, would be phased out for families with annual incomes in the
$10,000-$15,000 range.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>REGULATIONS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   States are encouraged to adopt health and safety standards in
line with guidelines included in the measure. These include
first-aid and other training of child-care providers and inspections
of institutional child-care settings. Immediate family members of
children who provide child care for them are exempt from any state
training requirements. Also, Social Security recipients would have
any child-care earnings exempted from outside earnings limitations.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CHURCH PROVIDERS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The bill allows federal subsidies to pay for child care at
church-run centers but prohibits the use of the funds for any
purposes inconsistent with the constitutionally mandated separation
of church and state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
