<FIRST>r w PM-OverchargeSettlement     06-24 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overcharge Settlement,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Connecticut Man To Receive $1.4 Million In Government Overcharge
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ball bearing manufacturer has agreed to pay
the government $14.3 million to settle claims the company
overcharged the Pentagon, and the Connecticut man who initiated the
charges will get a more than $1 million slice of the settlement.
   The Justice Department said Friday that George G. Butenkoff, a
former regional salesman for Industrial Tectonics Inc. of Dexter,
Mich., will receive $1,427,952.40.
   Under a provision of the False Claims Act, individuals can bring
fraud suits on behalf of themselves and the government and are
entitled to a percentage of any money the government receives.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown said Butenkoff's
settlement award is the largest of its type since the law was
revamped in 1986.
   Butenkoff, of East Windsor, Conn., did not return repeated
telephone messages Friday.
   Butenkoff filed suit in November 1985 in U.S. District Court in
Hartford, Conn., accusing Industrial Tectonics of overcharging Pratt
&amp; Whitney Aircraft for ball bearings delivered to the Air Force and
overcharged Westinghouse for bearings used in nuclear reactors by
the Navy. The military received the hardware between 1979 and 1985,
the Justice Department said.
   The government joined the suit in January 1986, and
investigations by Defense Contract Audit Agency supported the
claims, the department said.
   Robert L. Way, a spokesman for Axel Johnson Inc., a New York
company that purchased Industrial Tectonics in December 1982, said
most of the alleged overcharges occurred before the company was sold
and all came before Axel Johnson changed management at the Michigan
plant.
   Way said Butenkoff filed the suit after he was fired, but he
declined to discuss the circumstances around the dismissal.
   Way also said the settlement ``in large part'' comes from the
former owner, whom he declined to identify.
   The Justice Department said other claims against Industrial
Tectonics remain and will be resolved in administrative proceedings.
The department said those claims are expected to bring the
government more than $6 million.
   Way said the company denies the remaining claims.
</TEXT>
