<FIRST>r w PM-Pentagon-Unisys     06-24 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Unisys,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Suspension Lifted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Unisys Corp. will have to enforce ethical
standards for employees and improve contracting procedures under
terms of a deal with the Navy that caused the service to lift its
suspensions of three units of the defense contractor.
   The lifting of the suspension was announced Friday by the Navy
and involves the bidding rights of Unisys' Shipboard and Ground
Systems Group, the Computer Systems Division and the Communications
Systems Division.
   The Navy issued a statement which said, ``at the time of the
suspension, Unisys had initiated vigorous actions to ensure that
known individuals responsible for the misconduct were removed from
the company and that a disciplined program of self-governance was
put into place to guard against such abuses in the future.''
   ``The company had conducted an internal investigation; had
disciplined a number of individuals; and had adopted new procedures
and controls,'' the service said.
   Unisys was created three years ago by the merger of Sperry Corp.
and Burroughs Corp, a pair of firms whose chief products were
computers.
   Peter Hynes, a Unisys spokesman in Blue Bell, Pa., said the
company is pleased with the decision while discussions relating to
its involvement in the ``Operation Ill Wind'' defense procurement
investigation ``are in progress with the Department of Justice and
the company remains committed to reaching speedy resolution of all
issues relating to that investigation.''
   The ``Ill Wind'' probe includes allegations that private
consultants, hired by defense contractors, bribed Pentagon officials
to obtain inside information that gave companies an edge in securing
contracts.
   Unisys, the nation's 15th largest defense contractor, received
$1.4 billion worth of contracts last year from the Pentagon.
   Charles F. Gardner, former general manager for Unisys'
surveillance and fire control division on Long Island, is awaiting
sentencing next month on his guilty plea to bribery. Gardner has
been cooperating with the investigation.
   Robert D. Barrett, a Washington-based representative, also
pleaded guilty to concealing illegal political donations to former
Rep. Bill Chappell of Florida. Chappell, who died earlier this year,
was never charged.
</TEXT>
