<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FlagBurning     06-24 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Burning,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Bill Aimed At Circumventing Flag Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, angered over this week's Supreme
Court ruling that burning the American flag is constitutionally
protected free speech, passed legislation aimed at making
desecration of the flag unlawful.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., had the measure tacked onto an
unrelated child care bill late Friday.
   ``I'm confident it's constitutional,'' Biden, chairman of the
Senate Judiciary Committee and a leading congressional liberal, told
his colleagues.
   The move in the Senate came as several lawmakers introduced
constitutional amendments in the House following the Supreme Court
decision. House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said such attempts
should be taken cautiously and that it would ``be extraordinarily
slow to amend the First Amendment to the Constitution,'' which is
``at the heart of our constitutional liberties and freedom.''
   Biden said his simple legislation could accomplish the same aim
as a constitutional amendment.
   The bill reads: ``Whoever knowingly and publicly mutilates,
defaces, burns, displays on the floor or ground, or tramples upon
any flag of the United States shall be fined not more than $1,000 or
imprisoned for not more than one year, or both.''
   Biden's bill is identical to the federal statute on flag
desecration except it removes the words ``cast contempt.''
   The majority Supreme Court opinion reasoned that a Texas statute
on flag desecration violated the First Amendment because it was
aimed at protecting against acts toward the flag which would be
offensive to others. Biden's measure would treat desecration as an
act of vandalism without considering whether anyone was offended by
the act, presumably answering the court's First Amendment concerns.
   The House may consider next week a resolution similar to the one
passed by the Senate this week expressing opposition to the view of
the court.
   Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, a senior Republican on the House
Judiciary Committee, said he was also exploring ways of getting
around the decision without a constitutional amendment, possibly by
taking away from the Supreme Court jurisdiction over lawsuits on
flag desecration.
   ``I think the mood of the House is to do something effective and
not just pass resolutions condemning the burning of the flag,'' he
said. A new law would be simpler than a constitutional amendment, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890624-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China Bjt   06-24 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, Bjt,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Propaganda Specialist Takes Over China's Leading Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army propaganda specialist has taken over as
editor in chief at the official daily of the Communist Party in a
reshuffling of the newspaper's management, authorities announced
today.
   The replacements at The People's Daily came as the party stepped
up its propaganda campaign to defend the harsh suppression of
pro-democracy activists during a June 3-4 military operation in
which hundreds, perhaps thousands, of people died.
   The People's Daily is distributed to all offices and work units
throughout China. Its editorials, generally carried in other major
dailies, are regarded as party gospel in this, the world's most
populous country.
   During the past two days, the official press has also announced
arrests of 13 people the government describes as agents of Taiwan
with a mission to stir up anti-Communist sentiments.
   The foreign affairs office of the People's Daily said Shao Huaze,
director of the Propaganda Department of the People's Liberation
Army, had replaced Tan Wenrui as chief editor of China's leading
paper.
   The office also said Qian Liren, director at the daily, had left
his post. He was replaced by Gao Di, a senior official at the
Central Party School of the party Central Committee.
   Bot Qian and Tan resigned because of health reasons, the office
said without elaborating.
   The party has been increasing efforts to brand the activists as
``counterrevolutionaries'' and defend the recent arrests and
executions.
   More than 1,700 people have been arrested and 27 executed since
the nationwide crackdown began almost three weeks ago.
   Hundreds of journalists from all the major national dailies and
broadcasting stations participated in the pro-democracy rallies that
led to the crackdown. For a brief time in late May, the official
press was more independent than it had ever been in history.
   The press quickly reverted to acting as an unquestioning organ
for government and party propaganda after the military drive in
Beijing to quash the democracy movement.
   The Xinhua News Agency has said nearly 100 soldiers and police
died and that thousands were injured in that violence, while about
100 civilians died and nearly 1,000 were injured. Chinese witnesses
and Western intelligence sources said the death toll may have been
as high as 3,000.
   In other arrests, evening radio and television broadcasts said
Liu Xiaobo, an instructor at Beijing Normal University who recently
returned from six months in the United States, published
anti-Communist essays overseas and advocated abolition of the
Communists' one-party rule.
   China has denounced the United States for cutting off military
aid in protest of the crackdown.
   Congress has pressured President Bush to take stronger action,
but Bush's limited sanctions won praise from former President
Richard Nixon.
   ``If in our anger we drive China back into the shadows of the
Soviet Union and the oppressive economic system (senior leader) Deng
Xiaoping has tried to reform, those who have died for freedom in
China will truly have died in vain,'' Nixon said in an article
written for the Los Angeles Times Syndicate.
   As president, Nixon reopened the door to China with a visit in
1972.
   In China, the arrests of three more student and worker leaders
were also reported today.
   Authorities in the northeastern city of Jinan also arrested 40
people for joining in protests that rocked the city after the
military assault in Beijing, the People's Daily said.
   A Chinese source in Beijing said night-shift workers were ordered
to carry their identification papers in anticipation of more police
searches for activists. The report suggested police were preparing
another major sweep of arrests.
   There were reports, meanwhile, that the party Central Committee
was in session to formally oust party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang
and Hu Qili, another member of the powerful five-man Politburo
Standing Committee. However, they were impossible to confirm.
   One European diplomat said the meeting had taken place or was
about to convene, and results would be announced on Sunday. Other
sources said senior officials from the provinces were being flown
into a military airport in southern Beijing.
   Zhao has not been seen in public since May 19. It is believed he
opposed Deng's decision to impose martial law in Beijing and use
military force to crush the student demonstrations.
   Hu, who had directed party propaganda, is also believed to have
been pushed out because of his moderate stand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
