<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     06-24 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>River Water, Not Champagne Will Christen USS Jefferson City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The submarine USS Jefferson City will be
christened next year with a bottle of water from the Missouri River
instead of the usual bottle of champagne.
   ``The Missouri River is strong and determined in its course; the
USS Jefferson City will be sent on its course with the strength and
determination symbolized by the Missouri River water,'' Susie
Skelton, wife of Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo., who will christen the
submarine at its launching next year, said in a statement issued
Friday.
   The Defense Department says no regulations govern what is used to
christen ships, but champagne is most common because of the splash
and foam when the bottle breaks. Government historians told
Skelton's office that river water was used in 1858, when a bottle of
Connecticut River water was smashed over the bow of the steam sloop
USS Hartford.
   The launching of the submarine Jefferson City, tentatively set
for June 1990, will take place in Newport News, Va., where it is
being built.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Groups of Senators Visits Geneva, Vienna to Observe Treaty Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven senators will visit Geneva and Vienna
next week to observe US-Soviet arms control negotiations on nuclear,
chemical and conventional weapons.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., who is leading the delegation, said
Friday the delegation intends to remind Soviet negotiators in Geneva
and Vienna ``that the Senate will need to be confident that we can
prevent cheating in any successful treaty.''
   Lugar is co-chairman of the U.S. Senate Arms Control Observer
Group, which has monitored arms control negotiations since 1985. The
delegation was planning to leave as early as today, depending on
when the Senate could finish its business.
   The delegation will discuss strategic nuclear weapons at the
Strategic Arms Reduction Talks and examine prospects for eliminating
chemical weapons at the Conference on Disarmament, both in Geneva.
They will then spend two days at the conventional weapons talks in
Vienna before returning to Washington on June 30.
   Members of the observer group are Lugar, and Sens. Claiborne
Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee;
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska; Jake Garn, R-Utah; Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.;
Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.; Paul S. Sarbanes, D-Md.; John Warner,
R-Va.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; Don Nickles, R-Okla.; and Albert Gore
Jr., D-Tenn.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>GAO Says Navy Improperly Restricted Competition on Computer Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy improperly restricted competition on a
$30 million computer contract by setting specifications that only
allowed International Business Machines Corp. to bid, says a
congressional watchdog agency.
   The General Accounting Office found that the service, in a rush
to meet a December 1988 deadline, violated federal regulations when
it specified IBM hardware and related equipment in soliciting for a
payroll computer system.
   The Competition in Contracting Act and the Federal Acquisition
Regulation require that procurement specifications state only the
government's actual needs and promote open competition.
   The GAO also found that the Navy received a system design that
did not meet its payroll needs.
   Lt. Greg Smith, a Navy spokesman, said the service would reserve
comment on the report until it saw a copy.
</TEXT>
