<FIRST>r a PM-US-ChinaDissidents     06-24 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China Dissidents,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amid Beijing Protests, U.S.-Based Dissidents Fought Among Themselves</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN RUEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Chinese students mounted pro-democracy
protests in Beijing this spring, a government spokesman called a New
York group an instigator of the movement.
   ``The student demonstrations have two backstage directors: Fang
Lizhi and China Spring,'' State Council spokesman Yuan Mu was quoted
as saying in the Communist Party newspaper People's Daily.
   Both ``directors'' are doing little directing now, though.
   Fang, China's best-known dissident, has taken refuge in the U.S.
Embassy in Beijing. And China Spring, the U.S.-based exile group at
the forefront of the Chinese democracy movement the last six years,
has been racked by internal strife.
   The turmoil, in fact, climaxed this spring, blunting its impact
during the crucial moment in Chinese history.
   Since January, China Spring has taken its founder, Wang
Bingzhang, to court over bank transactions. The rift has kept China
Spring on the sidelines during the student protests that culminated
June 3-4 in Tiananmen Square.
   Founded by Wang in 1983, the group has been dogged by controversy
throughout its existence. Members of the Standing Committee often
change, and critics frequently accuse it of accepting funds from
Taiwan's ruling party, the Kuomintang.
   Yet, China Spring used an underground network of supporters in
China to smuggle out manuscripts by Fang and some of China's leading
political prisoners, giving the group stature. At its zenith, China
Spring claimed 50 branches on five continents.
   China Spring favors non-violent means to ``promote democracy and
improve human rights conditions in China with the ultimate goal of
transforming the totalitarian system into a democratic one,'' Wang
wrote in the group's magazine.
   Even supporters-turned-opponents credit Wang with having the
foresight to envision a grass-roots democracy movement in China.
   ``Wang is history. I give him credit for starting the movement,
but I think he finished his mission,'' says Feng Shengping, a new
leader of China Spring. Wang was expelled from the Standing
Committee last January. In a statement, China Spring said he
``seriously mixed up his public and private financial affairs.''
   In February, Wang struck back, taking out a full-page ad in World
Journal, the New York-based, Chinese-language newspaper. He denied
financial wrongdoing, and labeled two China Spring leaders as
``secret Chinese Communist Party members and Ministry of State
Security agents.'' Both men denied the accusation.
   China Spring won a temporary restraining order in March barring
Wang from withdrawing $73,000 he had moved from the group's savings
account to a separate account.
   In April, Wang's supporters broke away, forming a new faction
called the Chinese Democratic Party.
   Wang hopes relations can be improved among members.
   China Spring is holding a convention in Los Angeles, and more
than a hundred people are expected to attend. Wang left New York
Friday to attend the convention and said he hopes the convention
will lead toward reconciliation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
