<FIRST>r a PM-SeabrookShutdown     06-24 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seabrook Shutdown,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seabrook Low-Power Tests on Hold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seabrook nuclear power plant has
suspended low-power testing indefinitely after federal regulators
shut down the reactor because of a malfunctioning valve.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., a leading Seabrook opponent, said
Friday that top Nuclear Regulatory Commission regional officials
told him an NRC official had to grab a control room operator to get
him to shut down the reactor Thursday.
   ``What we have here is a situation where the Seabrook reactor
operators were not able to follow their own procedures, and an NRC
official in the control room, first having given a verbal
instruction, had to physically grab one of the Seabrook operators to
ensure that procedures would be followed to shut the plant down
immediately,'' Markey said in a telephone interview.
   ``That didn't happen,'' Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams said.
   Williams said operators already were aware of the problem when
the NRC official spoke up, and three minutes later decided to shut
down the reactor. No one was grabbed, he said.
   The commission believes operators waited ``several minutes'' too
long before shutting down the reactor at 12:36 p.m. Thursday, plant
executive Edward Brown said in a statement.
   ``We did not strictly adhere to our test procedures'' in response
to temperature and pressure changes in various systems, Brown said.
   ``At no time was there a risk to plant systems or the general
public,'' Seabrook spokesman Ron Sher said.
   NRC spokesman Frank Ingram said Seabrook's low-level testing
license is not affected by the incident, and the commission ``won't
say (operators) made a mistake.''
   Ingram said Brown agreed that the plant will delay resumption of
low-power tests until operators pinpoint why the valve malfunctioned
in the non-nuclear area, make any necessary repairs, and review the
actions with NRC staff.
   Ingram said he had no idea how long the process would take.
   A decade behind schedule, the bitterly contested plant won
permission to conduct low-power tests earlier this month. The tests
began June 13 and had been running smoothly.
   Dianne Dunfey, a member of the anti-Seabrook Clamshell Alliance,
said her group thinks the situation is more serious than Seabrook or
federal officials have said.
   ``Our feeling is that for the NRC, characteristically
irresponsible in their handling of problems of this nature, to take
this step ... indicates a very serious breach by operators,'' Dunfey
said.
   Gov. Judd Gregg said he was undisturbed by the situation.
   ``It is also reassuring to know that the NRC is taking the
necessary steps to ensure safe operations if appropriate procedures
at the plant were not followed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
