<FIRST>r a PM-LynchTrial     06-24 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lynch Trial,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Gets Life in Murder, Baby Snatching Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has sentenced a woman convicted of
killing a couple to steal their 9-day-old son to life in prison
without probation or parole.
   Joyce Lynch dropped her head and cried Friday when the verdict
was read.
   Mrs. Lynch, who could have been sentenced to death, was convicted
of killing Joseph and Beverly Gibson, snatching their infant son,
Matthew, and trying to pass him off as her own.
   The Kent County Superior Court jury deliberated less than an hour
before reaching the verdict.
   Mrs. Lynch, 36, and her husband, Richard, 27, named the infant
Richard Lynch III and showed him off to friends and family like
proud, new parents, according to the prosecution.
   Lynch also is charged in the 1987 slayings and is scheduled for
trial in September. The Lynches have accused each other in the
crimes.
   Mrs. Lynch, convicted Thursday, will not be formally sentenced
until her husband's trial is over, according to Deputy Attorney
General Ferris Wharton. The state had sought the death penalty for
Mrs. Lynch.
   ``I didn't feel as if she got what she deserved. I think she
should have gotten the death sentence,'' said Barbara Staats, Mrs.
Gibson's aunt.
   The Rev. Kenneth Valentine, spokesman for Mrs. Gibson's parents,
said the family was disappointed in the jury's decision.
   In arguing for Mrs. Lynch's life, public defender Duane Werb told
the jury that if they sentenced her to prison, ``she will be in a
place where she can harm no one.''
</TEXT>
