<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-HibariMisora 1stLd-Writethru a0435 06-24 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Hibari Misora, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Songstress of Japan's Postwar Recovery Dead at 52</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with critic's comments. CORRECTS
translation of stage name. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Hibari Misora, who symbolized Japan's postwar
recovery to millions of Japanese, died of heart failure this morning
after a lengthy illness. She was 52.
   The death of the woman some compared to the famed French singer
Edith Piaf topped the morning news, and television broadcasts were
filled with pictures of weeping fans and hundreds of reporters
crowding around her house.
   National television networks made plans to interrupt normal
programming this evening to broadcast special retrospective shows.
Within hours of her death, producers and critics dressed in black
funeral wear solemnly discussed her career on talk shows.
   ``It's a party's over kind of feeling,'' said music critic Toyo
Nakamura in a four-page special on Ms. Misora in the Asahi Shimbun
newspaper.
   Ms. Misora was a source of strength for many Japanese hopeless
and depressed after Japan's disastrous defeat in World War II, Masao
Yamaguchi, a professor at Tokyo Foreign Language University, told
Kyodo News Service.
   From her days as a child performer, her songs and popular image
cheered people and helped prompt Japan's recovery and economic
growth in the postwar era, he said.
   She had lost popularity in recent years as Japan's became a world
power, and people no longer seemed to need her, Yamaguchi said.
   Ms. Misora, a Yokohama fishmonger's daughter, made her singing
debut at age 11 in 1948. She was later celebrated for her renditions
of melancholy ballads such as ``Kanashii Sake'' (Sad Rice Wine) and
``Ringo Oiwake'' (Song of Apples).
   The Mainichi Shimbun newspaper said she was ``the queen of
singers until the end of her life,'' and that ``nothing else but her
death could be so shocking to many Japanese hearts.''
   Ms. Misora was born as Kazue Kato. Her stage name means ``skylark
beautiful sky.''
   She performed in the United States, including Hawaii, in 1950,
when she was 13. She ended her 40-year career with a 10-hour live
radio show by Nippon Broadcasting Co. on March 21, shortly before
she was hospitalized at Juntendo.
   Ms. Misora released 1,200 songs and sold 68 million records,
including 45 million singles. She received numerous musical awards
and was also known as an actress in many Japanese musical movies and
plays.
   She married actor Akira Kobayashi in 1962, but they divorced two
years later.
   Two years ago, she was hospitalized for four months in Fukuoka to
treat chronic hepatitis and a hip bone ailment.
   Since March, she had been hospitalized at Juntendo University
Hospital in Tokyo, where pneumonia contributed to her heart failure.
   A private funeral is scheduled for Monday, according to Columbia
Records, her record label. The public funeral will be held July 22.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
