<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Aflaq     06-24 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Aflaq,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aflaq, Baath Party Founder, Dead at 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michel Aflaq, the founding leader of Iraq's ruling
Baath party, has died in a Paris hospital. He was 79.
   Aflaq died Friday night after heart surgery on June 10, the Iraqi
Embassy said.
   A statement issued by the Arab Baath Socialist Party in Iraq said
Aflaq, who was born a Greek Orthodox in Syria, had converted to
Islam but did not want it known until after his death.
   Iraqi radio cut its regular programs and started broadcasting
Koranic verses after the announcement of his death was made in
Baghdad.
   He founded the party in 1947 with the late Salah Bitar as a
secular party advocating Arab unity and non-communist socialism.
   Aflaq was in and out of jail in the early 1950's as the party
struggled for influence in Syria. It took control there in 1963 in a
bloody coup.
   Factional fighting forced Aflaq to go underground in 1966 and
flee Syria. However, the party seized power the same year in Iraq,
and Aflaq was appointed secretary general. He worked out of Beirut,
Lebanon, but moved to Baghdad after civil war in Lebanon broke out
in 1975.
   He is expected to be succeeded by President Saddam Hussein as
general secretary.
   The Iraqi Baath party is now a bitter rival of the Syrian party.
   The party statement said Aflaq's body will be flown to Baghdad
for burial Monday. He is survived by a daughter and three sons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
