<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     06-24 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boat People Allowed Temporary Stay, Given Instant Noodles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials will let 78
Vietnamese refugees stay temporarily in South Korea after they
burned their vessel at sea to force authorities to take them ashore,
news reports said.
   The officials initially said the Vietnamese would be given a new
boat and towed back out to sea, the reports said Friday. But they
later decided the 45 men and 33 women could stay on Sangdo Island
off the south coast until their burned boat is repaired, the reports
said.
   The boat people burned their boat at sea on June 17.
   South Korea says its only refugee camp is already overcrowded and
the boat people cannot stay. The government said 1,057 Vietnamese
boat people have been resettled in third countries since the 1975
communist takeover in Vietnam. But 219 are awaiting resettlement.
   Local villagers have also objected to the presence of the
newcomers. About 100 villagers in 16 fishing vessels blocked patrol
boats carrying the refugees for five hours Thursday in an effort to
prevent them from landing, according to Yonhap, the South Korean
news agency.
   It said the villagers called off the protest after immigration
officials promised the Vietnamese stay would be limited to 30 days.
   The refugees were given five tents, 10 boxes of instant noodles,
rice, medicine, T-shirts, pants, towels and soap, Yonhap said.
</TEXT>
