<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0609EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DropoutCure     06-24 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dropout Cure,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quincy, Mass., Halves Dropout Rate by Tailoring School to Students'
Needs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dropout rate was halved after this
Boston suburb's officials lavished attention on potential dropouts,
offering day-care centers, vocational training for the disabled and
night classes for working teens.
   ``The secret is, a kid can't drop out without going through a
long program of help-providers,'' said Schools Superintendent Robert
Ricci on Friday. ``It's nothing that hasn't been done. But most
districts aren't that flexible. There's a blueprint here for urban
districts.''
   Ricci calculated the dropout rate by following a group of
students from ninth grade through the day they should graduate. The
traditional method is to compare senior classes from year to year.
By tracking ninth-graders, the schools can more accurately assess
whether programs are working, experts said.
   In Quincy, they apparently work.
   The 1987-88 class graduating lost 19.7 percent of its students.
This year's graduating class was down by just 10.9 percent, a loss
of 70 students out of 643 potential graduates.
   The success in retaining students came from a simple formula.
Said Ricci: ``They get a lot of attention and a lot of
alternatives.''
   Any eighth-graders thought to be potential dropouts receive
special counseling to help them make the transition to high school.
This is followed up through their ninth grade school year.
   Potential dropouts are usually a year or more older than their
classmates; behind in basic skill levels; or from families that are
poorly educated, school officials said.
   Quincy offers schooling for teen-age mothers by providing day
care for their babies, and vocational training for the disabled.
   The school schedule can be adjusted to the student's needs,
including part-time work combined with courses for credit at a
junior college or in Cambridge at the Harvard University extension
program.
   Students can work during the day and study for a general
equivalency diploma, or a GED, at night.
   If these inducements don't work, and a student is determined to
drop out, he is encouraged to take the GED exam. If he passes, he
can receive his diploma on graduation day. If not, he can take
courses to help him pass.
   Quincy is a largely blue-collar city of 89,000 people just south
of Boston. Its public schools serve 8,000 youngsters. The district
consists of two high schools and one vocational school. The program
was developed through policy changes and some reorginzation,
resulting in no significant budget increase.
   The Quincy results drew applause Friday from others concerned
with dropout prevention.
   Brandeis University professor Andrew Hahn, a labor market
specialist concerned with the problems of urban education, praised
the Quincy program.
   ``The dropout problem is something a lot of people are dealing
with. When you lose half your ninth-grade class in some of our
nation's largest cities, your community is going to suffer,'' Hahn
said. ``The best drop-out prevention program has the top
administrators involved. What is so notable (about Quincy) is that
the superintendent is so passionate about it.''
   In major cities the attrition rate can be 40 percent to 60
percent, school officials said.
   Halving a dropout rate is impressive, said Michele Cahill of the
Academy for Educational Development, an international educational
consulting firm in New York City that works with more than 40 urban
school districts on dropout prevention.
   ``What it seems like they're doing, that they've put in a really
good exit intervention,'' Ms. Cahill said.
   She said researchers are finding that it's the ``comprehensive''
programs that work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890624-0047 </DOCNO>
