<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-ZhaoProfile     06-24 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Zhao Profile,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zhao Ziyang Pushed for Reforms, Brought Style to Chinese Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zhao Ziyang moved into the political spotlight as
a disciple of senior leader Deng Xiaoping, successfully installing
economic reforms in Sichuan Province and bringing a progressive
style to the Chinese leadership.
   But with his ouster today as general secretary of the Communist
Party, Zhao ended up with the same fate as his predecessor _
stripped of power and disgraced for sympathizing with students
seeking democratic reforms.
   In his tailored Western suits, Zhao once represented the
emergence of a new brand of leader in China, a change from the
revolutionary heroes who founded the communist state in 1949 to a
new generation showing more interest in economic results than
Marxist ideology.
   Zhao, 69, took over as acting Communist Party chief in January
1987 after the ouster of Hu Yaobang, who also was considered too
sympathetic to student protesters calling for political reforms.
Nine months later, Zhao formally was named party chief.
   Hu's death on April 15 set off the student demonstrations in
Beijing. Now Zhao too has fallen from favor after showing support
for some of the demands of students and opposing the decision to
declare martial law in the capital. Zhao has not been seen in public
since May 19, a day before martial law was imposed.
   While tens of thousands of students occupied Tiananmen Square
last month, Zhao told visiting Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev that
Chinese people could enjoy ``genuine democracy'' under the 47
million-member Communist Party. He also said political and economic
reform should proceed at an equal pace.
   Like Deng, Zhao was purged during the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution, accused of being a capitalist sympathizer. In 1967 he
was dragged from his home in the southern city of Canton (Guangzhou)
and paraded through the streets with a dunce cap on his head.
   But he came out of the internal exile that followed to
energetically carry out Deng's market-oriented reforms, measures
designed to rebuild and modernize a country that had fallen apart
during the extreme leftism and repression of the Cultural Revolution.
   In 1975, Zhao became governor of Sichuan, the country's most
populous province. He dismantled communes and allowed peasants to
till private plots.
   The reforms ended food shortages that had people at the brink of
starvation. Under Zhao, the central province harvested bumper yields.
   Deng brought Zhao to Beijing in 1980 as a member of the party's
policy-making Politburo and vice premier. Six months later be became
premier and served in that post until picked to head the Communist
Party.
   He traveled widely throughout the world and earned a reputation
as an urbane and self-assured Chinese leader who was tough at the
negotiating table.
   Zhao was born in October 1919, the son of a wealthy landowner in
central China's Henan province. As with most Chinese leaders, few
details of his family life are known.
   He has been married twice and has four sons and a daughter, Zhao
Liang, who studied in Hawaii in 1981-83. He told reporters that he
worked 10 hours a day, jogged in the morning and argued with his
family at the dinner table. He also regularly played golf, a sport
once condemned in China as a luxury.
   Zhao joined the Communist Youth League in 1932 and became a full
party member in 1936, 13 years before the communists came to power
after chasing the Chinese Nationalists from the mainland. He headed
the Communist Party in his native county for most of the 1937-45 war
between China and Japan.
   While serving as a regional party official in the 1950's, he
orchestrated a purge in southern Guangdong province against cadres
accused of corruption, ties to Nationalist Taiwan and opposition to
land reform.
   In 1957, Zhao oversaw a ``rectification'' campaign in which
80,000 officials were banished to the countryside, where they worked
and faced criticism for their past actions.
   Zhao disappeared for four years after being purged at the start
of the Cultural Revolution, finally re-emerging as party secretary
in Inner Mongolia in 1971.
   Duing those chaotic years, he appeared opportunistic. At one
point, he called for exposure of Deng's alleged crimes in an
apparent act of self-preservation not uncommon in China's tumultuous
politics.
   By the time Deng reappeared and consolidated power in 1978, Zhao
was firmly tied to the reformers.
   ``We must not bind ourselves as silkworms do within cocoons,'' he
said in a 1979 speech. ``All economic patterns and conventions which
hold back the development of productive forces should be abolished.''
</TEXT>
