<FIRST>r a PM-CowboysCheerleaders     06-24 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cowboys Cheerleaders,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Fans Boo Skimpy Outfits for Cheerleaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new owner of the Dallas Cowboys football team
isn't getting many cheers for a plan to outfit the team's
cheerleaders in skimpier uniforms.
   Several of the team's cheerleaders say they had learned they
might be required to wear Spandex cycling shorts and halter tops.
They said that they also were asked to act as hostesses at parties,
fraternize with the team and appear in beer commercials.
   More than a third have walked off the squad in protest, but
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said Friday the furor is a
misunderstanding and he hasn't changed any rules or policies.
   He said violations of the cheerleading squad policies that
prohibited drinking in uniform and fraternizing with players would
no longer result in automatic expulsion.
   ``Let's count on the judgment of these wonderful people,'' said
the Arkansas oilman, who bought the team earlier this year. ``Let's
not depend on rules.''
   But he did concede that a change was being considered in the
cheerleaders' familiar uniforms of white hot pants, go-go boots,
blue shirts tied at the midriff and fringed vests.
   The Dallas Times Herald asked its readers to call in their
opinion of new outfits for the cheerleaders. The question was:
``Should Jerry Jones change the cheerleaders' uniforms and make them
fraternize with the team?''
   More than 93 percent said no.
   Only 208 callers sided with the Cowboys owner, while 2,808 called
in to say he should leave the uniforms alone.
   ``As far as the Cowboys Cheerleaders are concerned, they are the
best in the United States and the rest are some of the cheapest,''
said Lee Daniels, 65, of Dallas. ``I hope they keep the uniforms and
morals up, and keep it just like it's been for years.''
   Cornell Hill, 37 of Dallas, took exception to the cheerleaders'
current look.
   ``The uniforms look like a private school, or something,'' he
said.
   Cheerleader director Debbie Bond has resigned and 14 veterans
said they would leave with her. The 23 new members have until Monday
to decide whether to stay.
   Several Cowboys Cheerleaders said conditions had become too lax
since Jones bought the team in February, firing longtime coach Tom
Landry the same day. Under former owner H.R. ``Bum'' Bright, squad
members were not allowed to drink or even be photographed with
someone holding a drink while in uniform.
</TEXT>
