<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-24 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Esther Williams says women who are used to
wearing swimsuits without high heels should have a foot up on their
competition in a Texas beauty pageant.
   The aquatics and cinema legend, now 60, came to San Antonio for a
midnight swim and a peek at how her idea for a barefoot beauty
stroll works.
   Contestants in the Miss Texas USA 1990 Pageant will stroll down
the walkway in swimsuit competition, but won't have the assistance
of high heels to improve the shapeliness of their calves.
   Pageant co-producer Richard Guy says borrowed the idea from Ms.
Williams, who refuses to let any models presenting her swimsuit line
to wear shoes.
   ``Un-classy ladies are the only ones I've seen in heels and
swimsuits,'' said Guy, who has helped develop five consecutive Miss
USA winners.
   Ms. Williams said she was usually pictured barefoot in her 27
movies, ``because I was always about to go into the water.''
   The pageant producers ``thought it was the funniest thing in the
world that all my girls were barefoot,'' she said. ``But I told them
you can't swim in shoes. And those suits I make aren't called
walking-around suits.''
   The barefoot contestants will wear Esther Williams-designed
swimsuits during the competition in Saturday's preliminaries and in
Monday night's finals.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Super-absorbent diapers, Velcro and the Jarvik
artificial heart have two things in common: All were developed
through research in space, and they're among 100 items at the
largest-ever exhibit of ``space spinoffs.''
   Other spinoffs on display at the Museum of Science and Industry
are a teflon frying pan, heated ski boots and a bag of potato chips.
   But for several little boys at a museum ceremony Friday, the
spinoffs weren't what really caught their imaginations.
   They had their eyes on a flag.
   Astronaut Jerry Ross visited the unusual exhibit and donated an
official Museum of Science and Industry flag that he took into space
on the 1988 Atlantis space shuttle mission.
   ``Even though we put a little over 1.8 million miles on that flag
in four days,'' it's still in good shape, Ross said.
   Ross, 41, a native of nearby Crown Point, Ind., used to visit the
museum as a boy, and wanted to take along on the Atlantis mission a
reminder of a place that helped spark his interest in space.
   The flag was stored in a vacuum-sealed container underneath the
floor of the spacecraft during the December flight, Ross said. It
will be displayed permanently at the museum.
</TEXT>
