<FIRST>r i PM-Burma-Opposition     06-24 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma-Opposition,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Assemble in Hopes of Seeing Opposition Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of supporters of opposition
leader Aung San Suu Kyi violated martial law by taking to the
streets of Burma's capital a day after she was criticized by the
government, sources said today.
   Friday's gathering was one of the largest assemblies by
opposition supporters since military commander Gen. Saw Maung seized
power last September and his troops crushed dissent by killing
hundreds of people.
   Hundreds of thousands of people protested nationwide last year to
demand an end to a quarter century of military control of the
government.
   One Burmese witness reached in Rangoon said hundreds of
supporters of Aung San Suu Kyi clogged an entire street block near
the central market Friday after hearing rumors she would make a
speech there.
   She was instead campaigning outside the capital, and the people
dispersed after security personnel arrived, the witness said on
condition of anonymity.
   A Western diplomat, giving a slightly different account, said
thousands of people waited for the opposition leader near the
Rangoon General Hospital, and some chanted slogans. He said the
crowd dispersed after the arrival of security personnel and a
monsoon downpour.
   Saw Maung has allowed the formation of opposition parties and
pledged a general election next year.
   But he is apparently worried about the popular following of Aung
San Suu Kyi and her National League for Democracy, the diplomat
said, also speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On Thursday, government spokesman Kyaw Sann accused her and her
party of defying martial law and organizing anti-government
demonstrations. He said the party ``must bear the consequences of
irresponsible and illegal acts.''
   A day earlier, a man was killed when hundreds of people gathered
in northern Rangoon in a memorial to those who died at the hands of
government forces last year.
   The government's Radio Rangoon said a member of the security
forces opened fire when the crowd charged.
   Western witnesses said today that government security personnel
kicked women at the gathering and hit other people with rifle butts.
</TEXT>
