<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China 3rdLd-Writethru a0467 06-24 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0467,0897</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Chief Zhao Stripped of Posts, Shanghai Chief Named</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD quotes from communique, other details. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's Communist Party today ousted party chief
Zhao Ziyang, blaming him for the turmoil caused by the pro-democracy
movement and for dividing the party.
   Zhao, 69, an architect of a decade of economic reform, was
replaced by Jiang Zemin, the Shanghai party leader who cracked down
on demonstrations in his city. Jiang is also considered an advocate
of economic modernization.
   The replacement of Zhao as general secretary of the 47-million
member party was announced in a communique by the official Xinhua
News Agency. A change in party leadership had been rumored since the
military assault in Beijing on June 3-4 left hundreds and perhaps
thousands of pro-democracy supporters dead.
   Jiang has taken a hard line in dealing with the protests since
then. He moved swiftly to end large protests that broke out in
Shanghai, and three men were executed last week in Shanghai for
participating in riots. A total of 27 people have been executed
nationwide.
   Zhao is believed to have been purged for opposing senior leader
Deng Xiaoping's use of troops to quell student protests in Beijing.
Zhao has not been seen in public since May 19, and his whereabouts
were unknown today.
   The communique, issued after a plenary session of 276 regular and
alternate members of the party's Central Committee, said Zhao had
``unshirkable responsibilities'' for the recent political turmoil
stemming from huge pro-democracy demonstrations in the capital and
many other Chinese cities.
   It accused Zhao of supporting the turmoil and ``splitting the
party.'' It said Zhao caused ``serious losses to the cause of the
party.''
   The report on Zhao was read by Premier Li Peng, the conservative
who triumphed over Zhao in a party power struggle stemming from the
protests.
   The communique said Zhao was dismissed as general secretary, from
his post in the 17-member ruling Politburo and its Standing
Committee, from membership in the 175-member policymaking Central
Committee, and first vice chairman of the Central Military
Commission. He had served as premier before he was named party chief
in January 1987.
   Jiang, 62, served as mayor of Shanghai, China's largest city,
from 1985 to 1988, when he moved over to head the Communist Party in
the city. He entered the Politburo, where he was a collegue of
Zhao's, in November 1987.
   The communique said nothing about filing criminal charges against
Zhao, who has been accused of supporting a ``counterrevolutionary
rebellion.''
   The communique acknowledged that Zhao ``did something beneficial
to the reform, the opening of China to the outside world and
economic work.'' It said the party will ``look further into his
case.''
   The Central Committee also decided to remove Hu Qili, 60, from
the Politburo Standing Committee. Hu is considered a moderate who
also opposed the introduction of martial law in Beijing.
   Jiang is a technocrat who speaks Russian and English. In
Shanghai, he has actively worked to restore the city's reputation as
a financial center and to attract foreign investment to revive its
industrial base.
   Some earlier reports had suggested that Qiao Shi, a Politburo
member in change of internal security, would be named to replace
Zhao.
   The party also expanded the Politburo Standing Committee from
five to six members, replacing Zhao and Hu with Jiang, Tianjin Mayor
Li Ruihuan and economist Song Ping, head of the party Organization
Department.
   It also announced a reshuffling in the party's four-member
Secretariat, removing Zhao allies Rui Xingwen and Yan Mingfu and
replacing them with Li Ruihuan and Politburo alternate Ding Guangen.
The Secretariat is responsible for day-to-day operations.
   The new Standing Committee members are all regarded as strong
advocates of China's open-door economic policies with the outside
world. They are also likely to back Deng's attempt to unify the
party behind his hard-line stance toward activists and other critics.
   The communique said the Politburo met from Monday through
Wednesday and the Central Committee, which must make all formal
decisions on leadership positions, held its session on Friday and
today.
   The leadership changes have been expected since May, when the
pro-democracy student demonstrations split the party leadership and
triggered a power struggle between moderates and hard-liners.
   Deng, 84, came down on the side of the hard-liners, deciding to
declare martial law in Beijing on May 20 and ordering the military
attack on the city.
   Earlier today, authorities announced an army propaganda
specialist has taken over as editor in chief at the official daily
of the Communist Party in a reshuffling of the newspaper's
management.
   The foreign affairs office of the People's Daily said Shao Huaze,
director of the Propaganda Department of the People's Liberation
Army, had replaced Tan Wenrui as chief editor of China's leading
paper.
   The office also said Qian Liren, director at the daily, had left
his post. He was replaced by Gao Di, a senior official at the
Central Party School of the party Central Committee.
   Both Qian and Tan resigned because of health reasons, the office
said without elaborating.
   The replacements at The People's Daily came as the party stepped
up its propaganda campaign to defend the suppression of
pro-democracy activists.
</TEXT>
