<FIRST>r i PM-TurfBattle     06-24 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turf Battle,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revenge of the Lawn: Neighbors in Court Over Heels in Sod</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOLIHULL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of walking her dog in a
sly and vindictive manner across her neighbors' lawn has agreed to
pay compensation.
   ``This is what could be described as a neighbors' dispute that
had got out of hand,'' John McCann, the prosecuting counsel, told
magistrates on Friday.
   The court in Solihull, a suburb of Birmingham, heard that
Winifred Burrows, 71, and Lillian Priddy, 74, had discovered holes
in the lawn bordering their prize-winning garden.
   Seeking confirmation of their suspicions, they staked out the
yard one February night and said they saw Judith Abercrombie, 48,
strutting across their grass in high-heeled shoes.
   When confronted, McCann said, ``Mrs. Abercrombie said to her dog:
`Come on, let's go back and do it again.'''
   Mrs. Priddy and Mrs. Burrows called the police, who came to Mrs.
Abercrombie's home and asked her to come to the station. ``No
chance,'' she allegedly responded and was arrested.
   ``The prosecution case is that it was an act of intent, it was
not an accident or recklessness, and there have been ongoing
problems between the two parties,'' McCann said.
   A charge of causing damage was dismissed when Mrs. Abercrombie
agreed to pay 50 pounds ($78) compensation to the sisters and to
post a bond of 200 pounds ($310) to keep the peace for two years.
   ``I accept there was a confrontation on the night of Feb. 8, but
I have always denied, and maintain my denial, that I committed any
criminal offense,'' she said afterward.
   Mrs. Burrows and Mrs. Priddy donated the damages to the Police
Benevolent Fund in gratitude for the support of the police.
   ``We hope this will be the end of the matter,'' Mrs. Priddy said.
``Quite frankly, we feel sorry for her.''
</TEXT>
