<FIRST>r i PM-Iran     06-24 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Newspaper Says Khomeini's Son Should Lead Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran should be governed by a three-member
advisory board chaired by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's son, Ahmad,
an editorial in a government-run newspaper said today.
   The governing board also should include President Ali Khamenei
and Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, said the Tehran Times
editorial, which was carried by the state-run Islamic Republic News
Agency.
   The editorial said Ahmad Khomeini should be chairman of the board
because he was close to his father, the architect of Iran's 1979
Islamic revolution, and familiar with his thinking.
   ``This will surely enable the leader Ayatollah Khamenei, who
himself has been a very close aide and disciple of the imam, not to
lose sight ever of the late imam's trend of thought and action,''
the English-language editorial said. Iranians referred to Khomeini
as the imam, or supreme spiritual leader.
   Khamenei, 49, was chosen to succeed Khomeini as the country's
supreme leader a day after Khomeini, 86, died of a heart attack June
3. Khamenei's second term as president expires in October and the
constitution bars him from running again.
   Rafsanjani, the 55-year-old parliament speaker and commander of
the armed forces, is the only announced candidate in the July 28
presidential elections.
   The younger Khomeini, 43, had no formal political role but served
as his father's chief assistant.
   The Iranian news agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the editorial
referred to economic and other unspecified problems the country
faces.
   ``With the experienced aides in different areas, the leadership
can most definitely speed up the realization of the divine goals of
the Islamic revolution,'' the paper said.
   There was speculation before Khomeini died that the council he
set up to choose his successor would appoint a committee in his
place, but the majority selected Khamenei.
</TEXT>
