<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Kuwait     06-24 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kuwait,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>22 Convicted of Trying to Overthrow Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kuwait's state security court today convicted 22
people of trying to overthrow the government and sentenced them to
prison terms ranging from five to 15 years.
   Another 11 defendants, including a British national of Lebanese
descent, were acquitted.
   Most of the defendants belong to the minority Shiite Moslem sect
in predominantly Sunni Moslem Kuwait.
   The case was first reported when the indictment was released in
March, but authorities never said when the defendants tried to
overthrow the government.
   They include 18 Kuwaitis believed to be of Iranian descent, two
Iranians, nine Iraqis, two Lebanese, the Briton and one person whose
country of origin was unknown. The defendants included engineers,
teachers, computer specialists, electricians, laborers and a former
police officer.
   They were charged with belonging to illegal groups that sought
``to demolish the social and economic fabric of the country,''
spread ``destructive ideologies'' and defame the emir, Sheik Jaber
al-Ahmed al-Sabah.
   The indictment said they used public statements and ``writings,
sketches and pictures'' in their activities.
   Only 20 of the defendants appeared before the court during the
trial, which began on May 13.
   Court Chairman Mohammed al-Bannai sentenced them during a public
session attended by relatives of the defendants. The defendants
present smiled broadly but made no comment.
   Kuwait was a repeated target of terrorist attacks during the
eight-year Iraq-Iran war. The attacks were blamed on Iran,
predominately Shiite and opposed to Kuwait for backing Iraq.
   One case involved an attempt on the life of the emir in May 1985
when a booby-trapped car rammed into his motorcade and exploded. He
escaped with minor injuries, but five people were killed.
   Relations between Kuwait and Iran have improved since a
cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war went into effect in August. But the
latest case underscored Kuwait's determination to keep monitoring
the Shiite minority.
</TEXT>
