<FIRST>u a PM-OilSpill 2ndLd-Writethru a0476 06-24 1018</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0476,1043</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five-Mile Oil Slick Threatens Rhode Island Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with oil beginning to wash ashore;
nine, sted four, tanks ruptured; quote from diver; unloading begun; and
to retain 1st reference to DiPrete. Picks up 15th graf, `Richard Dreedan.'
SUBS 25th graf, `Capt. Bruce' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with tanker apparently
not in violation for not having pilot on board.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews worked today to contain 1 million
gallons of heating oil that spilled from a tanker and created a
five-mile slick that began washing up on the Rhode Island coast.
   White House officials arrived just hours after the
Providence-bound tanker World Prodigy, carrying 7.6 million gallons
of heating oil, struck a rock at Brenton Reef in Rhode Island Sound
about 4:30 p.m. Friday.
   Just a few hours later, oil spilled in a collision of an oil
tanker and a tugboat at the mouth of the Houston Ship Channel at
Galveston Bay, Texas. The accidents came three months after nearly
11 million gallons of heavy crude oil gushed into Alaskan waters
from the tanker Exxon Valdez, causing the nation's worst oil spill.
   Army helicopters surveying the Rhode Island shore this morning
confirmed that oil was washing ashore near Jamestown, said Robert L.
Bendick Jr., director of the state Department of Environmental
Management.
   Bendick said curiosity seekers in Jamestown who were hampering
cleanup efforts were removed from the town's picturesque beach,
across the harbor from Newport.
   The spill occurred one mile south of Newport and by today it was
five miles long. No harm to wildlife was immediately reported, but
all of the state's beaches were closed today.
   The Department of Environmental Management said they would remain
off-limits until the oil had been cleaned up.
   Boaters also were asked to stay in port. ``We don't want boats
churning up the oil slick,'' said Stephen G. Morin, chief of the
department's emergency response team. But the organizers said the
Salem Pro Sail Series will continue as scheduled today at the
Newport Yachting Center. The competition began June 21 and is set to
continue until Sunday.
   Vice Adm. Clyde T. Lusk Jr. of the Coast Guard said a team from
Mobile, Ala., and special skimmer ships were brought in to combat
the spill.
   Nine of the ship's 27 tanks were damaged, said Coast Guard Capt.
Eric Williams of the Marine Safety office in Providence.
   Tim Morgan, a diver who surveyed the hull of the 530-foot tanker,
said there is a 200-foot-long gash, as wide as five feet, along one
side. There are about 150 feet of dents and smaller holes on the
other side, he said.
   ``The damage is so extreme it's impossible to seal the vessel off
with any kind of soft patches,'' Morgan said.
   The Coast Guard began unloading the World Prodigy about 2:20
a.m., and Williams said the work could take up to a week.
   Cleanup crews initially strung booms around the slick and later
replaced them with booms with deeper skirts to pool the oil, said
Lusk.
   The White House, criticized for its response to the Alaskan
spill, reacted swiftly to the Rhode Island accident. President Bush
dispatched Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan and William Reilly, head
of the Environmental Protection Agency, to the scene.
   ``It's a big spill and in a very important place,'' Reilly said
at a news conference about 2 a.m. after federal officials met with
Gov. Edward DiPrete. ``Narragansett Bay is one of the crown jewels
of the country's ocean resources.''
   Richard Dreedan, a Bush assistant at the scene, said the
president has determined to ``do everything possible to respond to
this situation,'' adding, ``We've obviously learned something from
that situation'' in Alaska.
   The Providence port, where the ship sailing under a Greek flag
was heading, is about 25 miles from Newport via Narragansett Bay,
which feeds into the Providence River.
   John Civic, who lives near Narragansett Bay, witnessed the
accident.
   ``I'm looking and this guy was barrelling along and boom; he just
stopped dead in the water. He was moving pretty good, faster than
most,'' he said.
   Officials said the magnitude was far less than the Valdez
disaster in March. The amount was less, and No. 2 heating oil is
lighter and easier to recover than the crude oil that poured into
Prince William Sound.
   ``There still will be a mess on the beach, it still will have to
be sucked up with absorbent pads, but at least it's not like Valdez,
where you have to sandblast it, steam it off the rocks,'' said Morin.
   The odor of the spilled oil wafted through this tony seaside
resort, where the shoreline is dotted with mansions.
   ``Boy, it's enough to knock you off your feet,'' said Rhode
Island Secretary of State Kathleen S. Connell, who lives near the
shore.
   The ship's master was identified as Iakovas Georgudis by Chief
Warrant Officer Jerry Alfred of the Coast Guard in Newport.
   DiPrete said the skipper told him no pilot was aboard the tanker
at the time of the crash. He said the captain also said he made a
mistake in plotting the ship's course.
   Marine Safety Office officials said the ship had not come quite
close enough to the bay to require a pilot, but that the ship so
close that it was unwise of the captain to operate without one.
   ``It's kind of a gray area out there,'' said Chief Warrant
Officer Jerry Alfred, a Marine Safety investigator.
   The governor said the state planned legal action, although he
said it was too soon to talk about criminal charges.
   ``There was plenty of ocean there. There was no reason this
terrible tragedy had to happen,'' DiPrete said.
   Brenton Reef is a nautical landmark where America's Cup yacht
races were held for many years.
   The tanker began its journey in Bourgas, Bulgaria, on the Black
Sea, according to Lloyds of London. The Coast Guard said the ship is
owned by the Greek-based Ballard Shipping Co., but did not know who
owns the cargo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
