<DOCNO> AP890624-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Turkey-Bulgaria     06-24 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turkey-Bulgaria,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protest Denounces Expulsion of Ethnic Turks From Bulgaria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VEDAT ERDAMAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150,000 demonstrators today
demanded Bulgaria end oppression that has led thousands of ethnic
Turks to flee Bulgaria.
   The protest in Taksim Square was organized by the governing
Motherland Party and the opposition Social Democrat and True Path
Parties.
   Organizers said thousands of ethnic Turks who immigrated to
Turkey from Bulgaria traveled to Istanbul from many western and
Thracian cities to attend the rally, which was broadcast live
nationally on the state-run television.
   There were hundreds of red-and-white Turkish flags in the square,
and banners hung from surrounding buildings denounced Bulgaria and
its leader, Todor Zhivkov. Protesters carried banners saying, ``End
Bulgarian Cruelty,'' ``Freedom for Turks in Bulgaria,'' and ``The
New Hitler Zhivkov.''
   Political leaders addressing the rally protested the expulsion of
ethnic Turks by Bulgaria. The crowd chanted slogans such as
``Murderer Zhivkov, army to Sofia!'' and ``We want guns against
Bulgaria!''
   In 1984, Bulgaria began forcing ethnic Turks to adopt Bulgarian
names and forbidding them to speak their language or practice their
religion.
   Thousands of Turks began leaving Bulgaria after Zhivkov said May
29 that any Bulgarian citizen, including the 1-million-strong
Turkish minority, could leave the country. Three weeks later,
250,000 Turks had applied for passports, and 150,000 of them
reportedly received them immediately.
   In Istanbul today, Mumin Gencoglu, the head of the Federation of
the Association of Immigrants from Bulgaria, and Sevket Yilmaz,
chairman of Turkey's largest labor federation, condemned the
Bulgarian oppression and expressed solidarity with ethnic Turks.
   They said Turkey was ready to accept all ethnic Turks who wanted
to come, and they called on the international commnuity for support.
   More than 60,000 ethnic Turks have crossed into Turkey over the
past month, bringing whatever belongings they could carry.
   Bulgarian officials say seven people died in violent clashes with
security forces in May. But Western diplomats in Sofia estimate at
least 30 ethnic Turks were killed and up to 5,000 expelled
immediately after the clashes.
   Premier Turgut Ozal has called on Bulgaria and the United Nations
to guarantee that ethnic Turks who want to leave Bulgaria can do so
in peace. But Sofia rejects a U.N. discussion of its Turkish
minority, insisting that such an ethnic group no longer exists in
Bulgaria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890624-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-TheChinaConnection Bjt   06-24 1251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-The China Connection, Bjt,1250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business, Cultural and Educational Ties Survive the Turmoil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At Q Soft, Inc., in Tyson's Corner, Va., plans
for selling software in China are on the back burner.
   At an Agriculture Department laboratory in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
a scheduled research trip to China by an aquatic weed specialist has
been put on hold.
   But in Foxboro, Mass., executives of the Foxboro Co. are in
nightly touch by telephone and fax machine with Chinese colleagues
at the company's electronics plant in Shanghai.
   In Shenzhen, China, six employes of the San Francisco-based
Bechtel Group supervise construction of a 28-story Intercontinental
Hotel within walking distance of the Hong Kong border.
   At the Sackler Gallery for Asian Art in Washington and at the
Columbus, Ohio, Museum of Art, people are lining up to view Chinese
art exhibits, and plans for more such exhibitions are under way.
   And in New York, the National Council of Churches has begun
orientation sessions for 19 new teachers to teach English in Chinese
schools.
   The warming of U.S. Chinese relations, which began with pingpong
diplomacy, has blossomed into a patchwork of cultural and scientific
ties, about $14 billion a year in two-way trade, and investment of
some $3.4 billion in China by about 300 companies. An estimated
300,000 Americans visited China last year and more than 50,000
Chinese came to the United States. Approximately 62,500 Chinese
students have enrolled in American schools since the beginning of
the thaw in the early 1970's.
   President Bush is being criticized by some in Congress for not
acting more forcefully against the repressive tactics of Beijing,
and was quoted by a senator Friday as saying ``there was a long road
that was going to have to be traveled in that relationship and that
we shouldn't move precipitously.''
   Roger Sullivan, president of the U.S.-China Business Council,
supported the president's go-slow approach, but said trade relations
between the two countries will nevertheless ``be cut back
considerably.''
   ``He's not cutting the ties, but the Chinese are doing it
themselves, very clearly,'' Sullivan said in an interview.
   China and the United States, at odds since the Communist takeover
of the mainland in 1949, began their rapprochement with an exchange
of table tennis teams in 1971. President Nixon followed up with a
visit to Beijing in 1972 and diplomatic relations between the two
countries were restored in 1979.
   ``The effort that has been done since Nixon's time till now is
just going down the drain,'' said South Kousoum, deputy director of
the Asian-Pacific American Chamber of Commerce.
   Q Soft, the Virginia computer software firm, had reportedly been
exploring the possibility of selling its services to the Chinese
national transportation system.
   ``Because of what happened in China in the last few weeks, that
definitely puts China on the back burner for us,'' said Rawlein
Soberano, director of program development for the company. ``We are
not going to pursue it more actively until the political stability
there is firmly established and things improve that would encourage
us to pursue a viable business activity with that country.''
   Gerald Gleason, a Foxboro vice president, said its Shanghai
factory, employing about 500 people to make control systems for oil
refineries and power plants, had turned a profit every year but the
first since it opened six years ago as a joint venture with a
Chinese company.
   ``Everything was normal right up until a few weeks ago,'' he
said. The week after the shootings in Tiananmen square, the company
withdrew the American executive who is deputy general manager of the
plant. The other American employe on the scene, the chief engineer,
was already back in Foxboro on an assignment connected with his work
for the Chinese plant. The men's families were also brought out.
They are still in Foxboro.
   ``But they are in communication with the plant every night by
telephone, fax or telex and are participating in decisions and what
have you and the plant is running in a more or less normal phase,''
Gleason said.
   Gleason said he anticipated a good chance of normal operation,
although ``everything is problematical.''
   ``There is certainly a continuing risk that some sort of
sanctions could develop that would make it difficult for us to
operate, because of the pressure both from the left and the right in
the Congress on the president,'' he said. ``The president's present
position would not seem to threaten ventures such as ours.''
   From San Francisco, Larry Miller, a spokesman for Bechtel, said
its two major projects in China had not been affected. One is a
nuclear power plant at Daya Bay, about 50 miles up the coast from
Hong Kong, for which it is providing management services during
construction. The other is the $640 million hotel it is building in
Shanzhen. The company transferred the four Americans in its Beijing
office to Shanzhen after the disturbances, and Miller said a
decision is planned during the coming week on whether to send them
back. Meanwhile, a Chinese company in a joint venture with Bechtel
is keeping the Beijing office open.
   The United States and China opened a research laboratory in
Beijing in December to help find natural enemies of insects and
weeds that threaten crops in the two countries. Officials said the
Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences was expected to send
scientists to the Fort Lauderdale lab this year.
   ``Everything as far as I know is on hold until we receive word,''
Ted Center, a research entomologist at Fort Lauderdale who is the
lead scientist for biological control projects on aquatic weeds,
said. ``We had planned to have one of our scientists over there in
July, and that trip has been canceled pending further developments.
Nobody really knows what is going to happen.''
   Other joint U.S.-Chinese scientific projects include research on
rangeland weeds that are common in both countries, and an
arrangement by the Energy Department and the Chinese Academy of
Sciences to study the greenhouse effect.
   In Columbus, more than 300,000 people have viewed the ``Sons of
Heaven'' exhibition of more than 225 national treasures from 22
Chinese museums since it opened March 1.
   A show of brush-and-ink paintings by Wang Yani, a 14-year-old
Chinese prodigy, opens Sunday at Washington's Sackler Gallery, and
spokeswoman Susan Bliss said, ``We expect that the public will be
very interested and will be coming.'' The child artist appeared at a
preview at the gallery June 21.
   Marc Wilson, director of the Nelson-Atkins Museum in Kansas City,
Mo., who organized the exhibition, said planners feared that the
disorder in China might affect it, ``but so far there is no sign of
it.''
   ``If they had wished to stop her from coming over they could
have, but they didn't,'' Wilson said. ``She left well after the
trouble.''
   ``We are working with China on other projects, and we are
proceeding,'' he said. ``We are not getting cold feet. If something
happens to the projects, if they are postponed, canceled, put on the
shelf, whatever, it will be on the Chinese side, not our side.''
   At the National Council of Churches, Cynthia McLean, a specialist
in the council's China program, said orientation began Friday for
the group of new teachers for the English teaching program the
council has been conducting jointly with Amity, its counterpart
group in China, since 1985.
   ``We plan to send them in August,'' she said. ``Everyone has
complete freedom along along the way to decide that they don't want
to go, but we haven't yet had any pullouts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
