<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-China     06-24 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-China,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Residents Protest Crackdown on Dissent in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people marched through a shopping
district to the unofficial Chinese Embassy on Saturday to deliver a
petition protesting the crackdown on dissent in China.
   The two-hour rally and march by at least 5,000 people was the
latest expression of anger by this British colony over Communist
China's suppression of the pro-democracy movement.
   The crackdown, which has included arrests and some executions,
has intensified fears over the return of Hong Kong to Chinese rule
in 1997.
   Hong Kong protesters began their demonstration at Victoria Park,
where they gathered around a 33-foot-high replica of the ``Goddess
of Democracy'' statue, which stood in Beijing's Tiananmen Square
before the military moved in June 3-4 to disperse pro-democracy
demonstrators.
   After speeches decrying the arrests and executions in China, the
crowd marched through the Causeway Bay shopping district to the
local Xinhua News Agency office, which is Beijing's representative
in the colony.
   The marchers carried banners that read ``Support the Beijing
students' long-term struggle,'' ``Down with fascism,'' and ``Down
with Li Peng, Long live people power.''
   Li Peng, premier of China, is one of the hard-line conservatives
behind the suppression of the democracy movement.
   Leading pro-democracy activists in Hong Kong handed a petition
calling for the release of all those detained in the crackdown to a
Xinhua official. The crowd in front of the news agency's building
chanted, ``Protest! Protest!''
   Several marchers stopped and bowed in front of wreaths placed
across the street from the Xinhua building in honor of Chinese who
have died in the pro-democracy movement.
</TEXT>
