<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-YanitheProdigy     06-24 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yani the Prodigy,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Age Chinese Artist Opens Show at Smithsonian Gallery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tranquil world away from the bloody violence
in her native China, 14-year-old artist Wang Yani squatted barefoot
on the Smithsonian gallery floor and demonstrated with lightning
brush and ink strokes why she is called ``a very rare phenomenon
anywhere in the world.''
   It took the slight, muscular girl in jean shorts slightly more
than a half-hour to fill her 8-foot-by-4-foot sheet of paper with
pigments and ink, which she dripped, poured, smeared, dabbed and
delicately brushed as she danced back and forth.
   ``In Yani's hands, the brush sings and the ink dances,'' said one
observer.
   Yani created a scene of two playful black monkeys _ her favorite
animals _ gathering pears under the gaze of flitting songbirds and
plump, dour hens.
   She called it ``The Happy Partners In the Orchard,'' stamped it
with her name seals in red and shyly smiled for the first time, as
the hushed crowd surrounding her in the Arthur M. Sackler Gallery
burst into applause.
   ``I'm finished,'' she said through an interpreter. ``I'm very
happy.''
   Her display of extraordinary artistic talent took place at a
press briefing last week before a collection of 69 of her paintings
goes on display Sunday for a four-month engagement at the Sackler, a
Smithsonian museum of Asian art.
   The show, ``Yani: the Brush of Innocence,'' will appear at the
Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas City, Mo., from Dec. 16 to
Jan. 28 and will be seen at the Asian Art Museum in San Francisco
next March 7 through April 29.
   The exhibition was organized by the Nelson-Atkins museum and is
sponsored by the Chinese Ministry of Culture. The Chinese
government's violent crackdown on pro-democracy student
demonstrators in the past three weeks did not disrupt plans for the
show, as some Sackler officials had feared. Yani and her father flew
here from Beijing without incident.
   ``I have not felt there is going to be any effect on Yani in the
future,'' said her father, artist Wang Shiqiang, 44.
   Museum director Milo Beach said Yani is ``a true prodigy'' whose
fresh, spontaneous paintings of childlike humor and grace ``have an
ability to communicate that is not limited by geography or age.''
   She is the youngest artist to be honored with a one-person show
in Smithsonian history, Beach said.
   Jan Stuart, a Chinese art expert at the Sackler, said a prodigy
of Yani's gifts in the visual arts is ``a very rare phenomenon
anywhere in the world.''
   Born in a small village in rural Guiangxi province in southern
China, Yani started painting when she was 2. Her works were
exhibited in three Chinese cities when she was 4, and since have
been displayed in Japan, West Germany, Singapore, Hong Kong, London
and St. Petersburg, Fla.
   She has turned out an estimated 10,000 paintings, but never had
formal art training. She said she once took art classes in school,
but ``my work was disagreeable to my teacher, so I stopped going.''
   Her father, who is an oil painter, has refused to coach Yani and
even abandoned his own painting a few years ago to make sure she was
not influenced by his own style of Western realism. ``Teaching may
spoil her innate creativity,'' he said.
   ``Nature was her teacher,'' said Ms. Stuart. Yani said she was
intrigued by the animals at the local zoo, especially ``the monkeys
who are like children playing in kindergarten'' in the mountains and
gardens near her home.
   The exhibition starts with her brush-and-ink portrait of a
kitten, done at age 3, and includes a 35-foot handscroll titled ``A
Hundred Monkeys'' which she painted at age 9. As she grew older,
Yani's subjects have broadened to include her friends (``Yani's
Party''), flowers (``The Lotus Flowers Are So Pretty'') and
landscapes. Later, more complex works include ``Last Night I Dreamt
I Saw the Racing Egrets.''
   Most of Yani's paintings are stored in her home and none has been
sold privately, although 44 of the works that her family gave to the
Chinese government were sold to collectors, most of them in West
Germany, for an undetermined sum.
   Yani's father says he was told that four small Yani paintings
given to the Chinese postal service for a postage stamp design in
1983 were sold to an unknown stamp collector for $13,000.
   Yani will return to the Sackler in September to give painting
demonstrations for art teachers and school children. She will take
her paintings back to China, but may leave an original with the
Sackler, a museum spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
