<FIRST>r i AM-SpaceJunk     06-24 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Junk,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Investigate the Thing That Fell to Earth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISBANE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large chunk of spacecraft has been
found in a remote section of northeastern Australia, and authorities
said Saturday it may be part of a French satellite.
   The debris was discovered on a remote farm about 1,100 miles
northwest of Brisbane. A police spokesman in the nearby town of
Conclurry said a helicopter would retrieve the wreckage, which was
found Friday.
   ``It is definitely of French origin,'' said the spokesman,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He would not disclose the size but said a nearby resident who had
seen it described the object as very large with two attached
cyclinders and two parachutes.
   A Brisbane police spokesman was quoted by the Australian
Associated Press as saying the ``French space junk'' was from
``Operation Globus,'' but refused to elaborate.
   France is heavily involved in the production of the Arianne
rocket and is part of a European space consortium that has captured
almost half the world's commercial satellite business.
</TEXT>
