<DOCNO> AP890624-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-KochIndustries     06-24 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koch Industries,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Investigates Kansas Company Accused of Stealing Oil From
Indians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is conducting a criminal
investigation of a Kansas-based company accused of stealing oil from
Indian-owned wells, a Senate committee spokesman says.
   The probe stems from information about Koch Industries Inc.
gathered by a special investigating committee of the Senate Select
Committee on Indian Affairs, spokesman Sam Hirsch said Friday.
   ``This has been referred to the U.S. attorney,'' confirmed Koch
spokesman George Pearson.
   He said, however, that Koch officials and representatives of the
U.S. attorney in Oklahoma City, Okla., would meet before a formal
investigation begins.
   ``They (the U.S. attorney's office) will have to make a decision
on whether to prosecute,'' said Pearson, director of public
relations for Koch.
   He said they may drop the probe after hearing Koch's side of the
story. He said no date had been set yet for the meeting.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Nancy Jones, in Oklahoma City, said her
office could ``neither confirm nor deny the existence of an ongoing
investigation.''
   The special Senate committee focused on Koch, the country's
largest independent oil purchaser, at a May 10 hearing in which
witnesses said Koch employees purposefully mismeasured oil from
wells on Indian lands.
   In a 57-page statement issued June 8, Koch said the committee
``unjustly defamed Koch and caused severe damage to its reputation
and business.''
   The lengthy document reviewed, point by point, the accusations
against the 49-year-old oil company, which is based in Wichita.
   It said the figures the committee used in its allegations were
inaccurate, and that comparisons with other companies were based on
noncomparable statistics.
   ``The committee stands firmly behind the findings released in its
May hearings,'' Hirsch said. ``The committee's investigators caught
Koch employees in the act of stealing oil on six separate occasions.
   ``Koch gaugers and supervisors also admitted to committee
investigators that it was company policy to mismeasure oil,'' he
said.
   Hirsch said documents the committee subpoenaed from Koch and
almost 30 other companies corroborated the committee's findings.
   He said Koch executives were presented the findings during closed
depositions and their responses were cited in the public hearings.
   ``Koch was also given the opportunity to testify in our public
hearings, but they would have been subject, of course, to cross
examination by the attorneys who conducted our investigation,'' said
Hirsch. Company representatives did not testify at the public
hearings.
   Hirsch said the committee would review Koch's June 8 statement
before making its final report, sometime this fall.
   The special committee has been investigating all areas of Indian
affairs and came upon the Koch case while probing federal agencies
assigned to protecting Indian lands.
   Pearson said the company ``never received a formal, informal,
verbal or written invitation'' to testify.
   When asked if the company requested an opportunity to speak,
Pearson said Koch did not feel it would be in its best interest to
appear at the hearing because of its format.
   ``We can be hurt at a hearing,'' he said. ``They (the committee)
can't be.''
   In congressional hearings, witnesses usually submit lengthy
written statements for the record and then are asked to summarize
their comments, followed by questioning from the members of Congress
and staff.
   Pearson said that, unlike in a court of law, those being
questioned have limited means to defend themselves and could be
greatly damaged if the hearing were televised.
   In its June 8 statement, Koch said the committee used ``anecdotal
evidence which was misleading at best and false at worst'' at the
hearing.
   Of witness Mary Limpy, a homeless Cheyenne-Arapaho, Koch said,
``Her problems obviously lie elsewhere and to suggest to this poor
lady that Koch is at fault is the height of demagoguery.''
   The woman claimed her financial problems stemmed from infrequent,
low royalty payments and that the leases on the wells in which she
had part interest were sold to Koch.
   ``We heard that the well had been capped for two years, but that
someone was stealing our oil because people saw trucks coming and
going from the allotment,'' Limpy said in her testimony.
   Pearson said Tenneco owned the leases and Koch bought the oil
from Tenneco. He said the wells were never capped.
   He also pointed out that many people had interests in the wells
and Limpy's share was a small fraction of the amount Tenneco paid
out to those people, explaining her small payments.
   Two other witnesses, Thurmon Parton and Arnita Parton Gonzalez
testified their royalty checks dropped from $3,000 to $1,000 a month
when Koch became involved with their leases. According to the
company's statement, the brother and sister saw an increase in their
payments.
   Koch officials blamed a dissident family member, William I. Koch,
for the trouble, saying he had a ``vendetta against Koch
Industries.''
   One of the witnesses who testified was an investigator who had
worked for William Koch, but a spokesman for William Koch said the
Senate committee made the first contact.
   ``In their zeal to get an oil company, and particularly one that
was politically unimportant, the staff obviously seized upon the
distorted information provided by William I. Koch, embellished it
with incorrect numbers, and, by withholding or ignoring evidence
favorable to Koch, produced a totally unfair and one-sided
hearing,'' Koch asserted in its statement.
</TEXT>
