<DOCNO> AP890624-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CatastrophicCoverage     06-24 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Coverage,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Finance Committee To Consider Cutting Tax; Making Program
Optional</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 5:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said Saturday he will
propose cutting the surtax Medicare-eligible Americans pay for the
new catastrophic illness insurance, and said the Senate Finance
Committee also will consider making the program voluntary.
   Despite opposition from the Bush administration, Bentsen says
he's backing a ``substantial cut'' in the Medicare catastrophic
so-called supplemental premium that is based on income.
   The Finance chairman raised the possibility of cutting the tax
several months ago if projections of large surpluses in the
catastrophic fund were borne out. However, he previously had stopped
short of saying he actually would propose a rollback.
   Enacted less than a year ago, the catastrophic tax has been under
heavy fire from many older Americans in upper-income ranges and
those who receive catastrophic insurance protection paid by the
current or former employers.
   Bentsen said the panel will meet in July to consider reducing the
tax as well as making catastrophic health care coverage voluntary by
linking it to Part B of Medicare _ the physician payment program
that is financed 75 percent with general federal tax money.
   Since enacted this year, the catastrophic tax is estimated to
produce a surplus of $2 billion to $4 billion, Bentsen said.
   ``I just don't think that the government ought to be making a
profit off of the patients or the beneficiaries of this program, or
to use that surplus to try to balance the budget,'' said the Texas
Democrat.
   ``So I've set a hearing for July that will cover these points and
to decide whether it should be made voluntary again, and, in turn,
I'll be recommending a substantial cut in the premium,'' Bentsen
said.
   Under the Senate's original plan, beneficiaries would have been
able to drop Medicare coverage of physician fees and catastrophic
insurance. But by the time the bill was finally approved, the
catastrophic coverage was mandatory.
   Bentsen has yet to announce his position on the issue of making
catastrophic coverage optional.
   The surtax this year is 15 percent of a Medicare beneficiary's
federal income tax of $150 or more.
   It is currently estimated that 59 percent of all beneficiaries
will pay no supplemental premium in 1989, above the $4 basic fee,
Bentsen's office said.
   Only 5.6 percent will pay the maximum surtax, set this year at
$800, Bentsen's office said.
   The surtax is scheduled to be phased in through 1993; by then, it
could reach 28 percent of a beneficiary's federal income tax of $150
or more.
   During the five years ending in 1993, the Congressional Budget
Office now estimates, the surtax is likely to bring in about $10
billion more than is expected to be paid for catastrophic benefits.
   But administration officials have cautioned that the surplus may
never exist, because the new program of catastrophic drug benefits
starting in 1991 could cost far more than previously estimated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
