<DOCNO> AP890624-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Beijing Bjt   06-24 0895</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beijing, Bjt,0930</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veneer of Calm Settles Over Tense Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   On the surface it is life as usual in Beijing.
Beneath the surface there is fear _ of sudden arrest, of the knock
on the door that means imprisonment or worse. Here is a report on
Beijing by an AP correspondent who reported on the pro-democracy
demonstrations and the army crackdown.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiananmen Square has been scrubbed clean of the
blood and ashes that stained it the night of June 3-4, when
thousands of soldiers crushed student-led protests for a freer
society.
   The only signs of the violence are watchful soldiers brandishing
automatic rifles, bullet holes in walls and scars left in the road
by marauding army tanks.
   The burned-out hulks of hundreds of public buses and army trucks
have been towed away. New flower beds and freshly painted traffic
dividers and garbage bins adorn the 100-acre square, still closed to
the public.
   Many Chinese say it's only window dressing.
   ``On the surface it's calm, but below that it's very tense,''
said a college student in Beijing who participated in the
demonstrations at Tiananmen. ``Many people are worried they might be
arrested, like me.''
   More than 1,600 have been arrested since the crackdown began, and
27 people have been executed.
   The government has demonstrated an ability for surveillance never
so chillingly revealed in 40 years of communist rule. Television
news has shown secretly shot videotapes of people authorities say
spied for Taiwan, China's longtime enemy.
   Most scenes were of Tiananmen Square, where the accused were
shown watching marches along with hundreds of thousands of other
people.
   The message seemed to be that anybody could be on those tapes,
and anybody could be charged with being a counterrevolutionary.
   Resignation and sullen indifference have replaced the grass-roots
fervor that initially stopped the tanks of the People's Liberation
Army from advancing on Beijing.
   Many businesses still are running at half-pace, and much of
Beijing's usual ``floating population'' of 1 million peddlers and
outsiders looking for work has retreated to the countryside.
   ``Only about half the normal number of people are here,'' said a
sales clerk at the Dongan Market on the normally jammed Wangfujing
shopping street. ``Nobody is coming in from the provinces.''
   Tibetan merchants who once hawked monkey skulls, tiger and bear
paws and other animal parts for medicinal uses outside a foreigner's
compound have disappeared.
   Scarlet banners calling for people to support the Communist Party
and respect the army flutter from hotels, construction cranes and
overpasses.
   A month ago, Westerners in Beijing were symbols of freedom and
hope.
   ``America is great,'' people would say heartily, flashing
thumbs-up signs. ``Your democracy is the best in the world.''
   Crowds would part to let foreign journalists see insulting
caricatures of Chinese leaders or photograph corpses after the June
3-4 violence, which official Chinese reports say killed 200 to 300
people, including many soldiers. Chinese witnesses and Western
intelligence sources said the death toll may have been as high as
3,000.
   An AP reporter who was chased and shot at by two soldiers for
photographing marching troops was cheered by a crowd when he emerged
from a parking lot where he had been hiding behind a van.
   Now foreigners are shunned.
   Commuters wheeling their bicycles past memorials for two soldiers
killed in the crackdown edged away uneasily when an American
approached. Large signs tell how the two soldiers were thrown off
bridges and, when they didn't die, set on fire by angry mobs.
   Witnesses said one soldier had shot to death a child and the
other had shot unarmed adults.
   ``Please don't sit here,'' a customer at an all-night restaurant
asked a Westerner. ``They see us talking to you and they'll haul us
in.''
   The proprietor of a nearby restaurant was bolder, inviting an
American to sit down and chat. Moments later, a platoon of soldiers
marched by and its officer said, ``Get these tables off the
sidewalk. They'd better be gone when we come back.''
   ``Let them come back, what do we care,'' said the manager. But he
moved the tables.
   Most people have become accustomed to the soldiers, who stare
blankly out from under their helmets as they stand guard at street
corners or patrol boulevards and back alleys.
   ``I'm just eating, I don't care about them,'' said a young man at
a restaurant on Changan Avenue, Beijing's main thoroughfare. ``They
mind their business and I mind mine.''
   Newscasts continue to show army officers, workers and even
students denouncing the pro-democracy movement, and there are signs
the propaganda campaign is working.
   ``There were a certain number of bad elements on the streets,''
said a 67-year-old man who has been repairing shoes on sidewalks for
50 years. ``The soldiers aren't after me, they're not after you.
They're after the evildoers.''
   But non-believers are legion.
   ``Not a single shot was fired in the square, and not one person
died there,'' said a hired driver, reciting the government line.
``That's all we're allowed to say.''
   Those who were on the streets or within earshot of the thunderous
rifle reports of June 3-4 say they will never forget.
   ``This used to be our square of democracy,'' a college student
said, looking across Tiananmen toward the Great Hall of the People.
``Now it's their square of dictatorship.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
