<DOCNO> AP890624-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SmogPlan     06-24 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smog Plan,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Board Refuses To Adopt Southern California Smog Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stringent air cleanup plan considered by
some a model for the nation has been shelved at least temporarily by
state officials who fear it won't work unless it gains wider support.
   The state Air Resources Board, citing mistrust between regional
air quality officials and business and environmentalist leaders,
voted 6-1 Friday to postpone action on the plan for 60 days.
   ``I'm troubled by the perceptions of this plan I continue to hear
from business and local government,'' said Jananne Sharpless, the
board's chairwoman.
   The plan would cut emissions from vehicles, businesses and
residences about 80 percent in an effort to make the air in Southern
California healthy again by 2007. It would also place restrictions
on the use of such consumer products as aerosol sprays and barbecue
lighter fluids.
   Officials of the South Coast Air Quality Management District,
which encompasses Los Angeles County and three counties to the south
and west, have estimated the plan would cost $2.6 billion a year.
Business estimates have placed the cost as high as $12 billion.
   In delaying a vote, the board ordered the district to outline how
it plans to account for the costs businesses will face. The board
also wants to know how cities and counties will be persuaded to
cooperate in enforcement.
   ``We have to ensure this plan can be implemented,'' Ms. Sharpless
said. ``We want a plan that works.''
   If adopted by the state board, appointed by Gov. George
Deukmejian, the plan also would require approval from the federal
Environmental Protection Agency.
   Ms. Sharpless, who is Deukmejian's environmental affairs
secretary, said the governor did not advise her to reject the plan,
but said he wanted the concerns of business better addressed.
   ``The governor is concerned about the impact on the economy,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
