<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BrothersShot     06-24 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brothers Shot,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Before Killing Himself, Boy Called Shooting `a Nightmare'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before turning the gun on himself, a
14-year-old boy wrote a note to his mother saying that shooting his
12-year-old brother to death was ``a nightmare,'' authorities say.
   ``Mom, I accidentally shot Clay. It's a nightmare, so I killed
myself,'' read the note that Damien Bienash left on the back of a
cash register receipt on the dining room table.
   The one-line statement was found when the boys' mother, Judy
Bienash, 36, returned home Thursday afternoon and found the bodies
of her sons Damien and Clay.
   Police and Rock County's chief deputy coroner, Richard Messner,
concluded that the deaths were a murder-suicide although friends and
relatives of the victims disputed the notion.
   Authorities said a quarrel over baseball cards may have led
Damien to shoot his younger brother with a gun that had been a gift
to the older boy from his father.
   ``There are only two people who could tell us why it happened,
and they are both dead,'' Police Lt. Larry Loveland said.
   But Christine Dunham, an aunt, said Friday that the incident
``was an accident, a total accident. It is not like them at all.
They loved each other too dearly. They always looked out for each
other.''
   According to police reports, Clay was shot ``basically square in
the face,'' indicating the shot from Damien may have been aimed. A
knife was found near Clay's right hand, and there were signs,
including a large fan that was tipped over, that indicated there may
have been a struggle, Messner said.
   A number of baseball cards were found on the floor near Clay's
feet.
   Police said the boys were quarreling over baseball cards before
their mother left earlier in the day.
   ``Clay, apparently, was an avid baseball card collector,''
Loveland said, ``and Damien grabbed a handful of them. That may not
have been the cause (of the shooting), but that's the last thing the
mother saw.''
   ``Apparently they had had altercations off and on,'' Messner
said. ``I think they were awfully good kids, but had altercations a
little more often than normal.''
   Messner said a single-shot, 20-gauge shotgun, a gift to Damien
from his father, was used in the shootings. The parents are
divorced. The boys' aunt said the boy had taken a hunter safety
course.
   The deaths, coupled with a shooting in Milwaukee on Thursday
evening in which a boy critically wounded a friend while playing
with a gun, led to renewed calls at the state Capitol for a
Florida-style gun law.
   The law passed last week in Florida after a spate of child
shootings there imposes penalties on adults who allow loaded weapons
to come into the hands of children and allows authorities to
prosecute the adult for a felony if a child's play with a weapon
results in death or injury.
</TEXT>
