<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-24 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians, Syrians Trade Heavy Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners on Saturday
fought their fiercest artillery duels in a month around Beirut and
the surrounding mountains. Police said three people were wounded.
   A police spokesman said the shelling declined after daybreak into
intermittent mortar exchanges across the capital's dividing Green
Line.
   He said two men and a woman were wounded before dawn in Christian
east Beirut, which was hammered all night by Syrian gunners deployed
in the city's western Moslem sector.
   The casualty toll from the 14-week confrontation between
Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's units and the Syrians
stood at 373 people killed and 1,460 wounded.
   The coastline north of Beirut took the brunt of the Syrian
barrage, which was aimed at maintaining a blockade of the
310-square-mile Christian heartland.
   A police spokesman said Aoun's gunners fired back at Syrian
artillery emplacements along west Beirut's seaside boulevard.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with police rules,
said about 520 shells and rockets exploded in Beirut's two sectors
and the Christian coastline in a 12-hour period.
   It was a sharp escalation of the daily shelling that has marked
the Syrian-Christian confrontation since an Arab summit called for a
cease-fire on May 26.
   The fierce clashes followed Aoun's call Friday for international
pressure on Syria to lift its siege of the Christian enclave.
   The Syrians began battering the area March 14, eight days after
Aoun ordered a blockade of illegal ports run by Syrian-backed
militias south of Beirut.
   Syria keeps 40,000 troops stationed across 70 percent of the
country under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   Moslem and Christian governments have been competing for power in
Lebanon since September, when outgoing President Amin Gemayel named
Aoun head of an interim Christian cabinet.
   Moslems and leftists refused to accept Aoun's appointment and
pledged allegiance to acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni
Moslem who governed during Gemayel's presidency.
   Meanwhile, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, said it
lost five ``martyrs'' in a confrontation with Israeli troops and
allied militiamen of the South Lebanon Army in the Bekaa valley on
Friday.
   The party said four of its fighters were wounded and four others
were missing.
   About 1,500 Hezbollah members chanting ``Death to America, death
to Israel,'' took part in a funeral procession in the Bekaa valley
town of Mashgara for the slain guerrillas.
   The Moslem cabinet in Lebanon's dual government said in a
statement it instructed Lebanon's U.N. envoy, Rachid Fakhoury, to
lodge a complaint with the U.N. Security Council about the ``Israeli
aggression.''
   Lebanese police said about 300 Israeli soldiers and South Lebanon
Army militiamen in 35 armored personnel carriers launched the sweep
of Hezbollah strongholds.
   Israeli military officials said Friday four guerrillas were
killed and one Israeli was slightly wounded in the clash.
</TEXT>
