<DOCNO> AP890624-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Committee     06-24 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Committee,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three New Faces on Standing Committee Lineup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of the six members of the
Standing Committee of the Communist Party Politburo, the
highest-ranking political body in the nation.
   _Li Peng, 60. Promoted to premier from vice premier in 1987, the
hard-line Li and senior leader Deng Xiaoping were behind the
decisions to impose martial law in Beijing and send in troops to
suppress pro-democracy demonstrators. A Soviet-trained technocrat,
Li spent most of his career in power and engineering fields. He
served as minister of the power industry and joined the party's
Central Committee in 1982 and the Politburo in 1985. He is the
adopted son of former Premier Chou En-lai and his widow, Deng
Yingchao.
   _Jiang Zemin, 62. Named Saturday to replace ousted Communist
Party chief Zhao Ziyang, Jiang is a former mayor of Shanghai,
China's largest city, and Shanghai's party chief since 1988. He took
a firm stance against the pro-democracy protests that spread to
Shanghai, where the first death sentences during the uprising were
meted out. He generally is aligned with the economic moderates who
support the open-door policy toward foreign investment and
revitalizing industry. Jiang is reportedly a son-in-law of former
President Li Xiannian, who backed the martial law order and
subsequent suppression of the democracy movement.
   _Qiao Shi, 65. He was considered the front-runner to take Zhao's
place as party chief because of his prominent role in party and
government functions after the June 3-4 crackdown on the protesters.
Head of the party's security apparatus and other powerful party
departments, little is known of his political leanings, though he is
believed to be a political conservative and neutral on economic
reform. He has been a party member since he was 16. Like many
Chinese officials, Qiao was purged during the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution. He re-emerged to head the party's International Liaison
Department in 1981. He was elected to the Politburo in 1985, became
a vice premier in 1986 and joined the Standing Committee in 1987.
   _Yao Yilin, 72. The senior vice premier, Yao is considered a
pragmatist on economic reform though he is associated with the
political conservatives. A specialist in trade and commerce, Yao was
a pro-communist student activist at prestigious Qinghua University.
He was a regional party official during the 1937-45 war with Japan
and later joined the trade ministry. He was named minister of
commerce in 1960, purged during the Cultural Revolution, and renamed
to the post after that decade of revolutionary turmoil. He was named
a vice premier in 1979 and was minister of the State Planning
Commission from 1980-83.
   _Song Ping, 72. Having studied agriculture at Beijing and Qinghua
Universities, Song was among the better educated of the early
revolutionaries. He held a variety of ideological and bureaucratic
posts and moved to the State Planning Commission in 1952, the Gansu
provincial military command area in the 1970s and returned to
Beijing to be vice minister of the planning commission in 1981.
Responsible for economic planning in the 1980s, he presented
economic reports to the National People's Congress four times. Most
recently he was head of the party's Organization Department.
   _Li Ruihuan, 54. An ex-carpenter and model worker, Li has been
Tianjin's mayor since 1982. He spent much of his career in
construction- and timber-related fields. He joined the Politburo in
1987 and has since been regarded as one of China's rising new
leaders. In 1980 Li was appointed secretary of the Communist Youth
League, and in 1982 he became vice mayor of Tianjin. As mayor he has
actively promoted foreign investment and increased foreign trade
through Tianjin, a major port city. His carpentry background has
earned him the nickname ``Luban,'' a demigod who protected
construction workers in Confucian times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
