<DOCNO> AP890624-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-HighwayCollapse     06-24 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Collapse,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 31 Die, 50 Hurt as Highway Collapses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 31 people died Saturday
and 50 were seriously hurt when a rural highway caved in and two
crowded buses tumbled into a 100-foot hole, rescue officials said.
   The accident occurred at 2:30 a.m. near the rural town of
Estancia, about 1,150 miles northeast of Rio de Janeiro. Estancia is
in the state of Sergipe.
   The buses, each jammed with 48 travelers, were making the
56-hour, 2,030-mile trek from the southeastern city of Sao Paulo to
Natal, federal police officer Luis Fernando Borges Santos told The
Associated Press by telephone from Estancia.
   ``They were riding along a high ridge when the road simply gave
way beneath them,'' said Borges Santos, who assisted rescue workers
at the scene. ``A hole the diameter of two buses opened up and
sucked them down the drop. It's pitch black out on that highway _
the drivers probably never saw a thing.''
   ``It's a miracle anyone survived at all,'' he said.
   One driver was killed, and the other was pulled from the wreckage
by rescue workers, Santos said.
   A rescue team of 50 civil and federal police and firefighters was
digging through the mud in search of bodies and possible survivors.
   ``We've pulled 31 mutilated corpses from the mud and we think
there must be dozens more buried underneath,'' said Santos. He said
no foreigners were on board the buses.
   TV film footage on Globo TV, the nation's largest commercial
network, showed helmeted rescue workers with spades and hoes hacking
through earth and pulling mud-covered bodies from the wrecks.
   Firefighter Carlos Enrique de Oliveira told the AP that heavy
rains in the region over the past week probably caused the highway
to fall away.
   ``That region is hilly and the earth beneath on both sides of the
drop that runs alongside the highway was already loose and
crumbling,'' said de Oliveira. ``The rains turned the ground into
putty.''
</TEXT>
