<DOCNO> AP890624-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1506EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Jiang     06-24 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jiang,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jiang is Liberal on Economic Reforms, Against Political Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jiang Zemin, the new leader of the world's largest
Communist Party, has been a leader in efforts to open China's
economy to the world, but he opposes political reform.
   Jiang, 62, on Saturday was named general secretary of the
47-million-member Communist Party of China. He replaces Zhao Ziyang,
who was ousted in disgrace for expressing sympathy for the
pro-democracy movement.
   Jiang's selection to the nation's most powerful post came as a
surprise to many China watchers. Although he has the experience and
the right political stance for the job, he lacks a power base.
   ``His base is his popularity, but in China that's not enough,''
said one Chinese source in Hong Kong who is familiar with Jiang's
family. ``He has no organizations behind him, like the military or
the state security organs.
   ``If the senior leaders want him to do something, he'll have no
choice.''
   Jiang has been party secretary of Shanghai, China's largest city,
and a member of the 17-member Politburo, the party's top
decision-making body.
   From 1985 until last year he was mayor of Shanghai, aggressively
promoting it as a financial and foreign investment center and
tackling the daunting transportation and housing problems of the
city of 12 million.
   ``Jiang is politically hard-line and economically liberal,'' said
the Chinese source.
   ``He likes good food and dresses well, too. He is very smooth,
very suave, a likable man.''
   Among the joint ventures Jiang has brought to his city are the
Shanghai Hilton, one of China's most luxurious hotels. He has also
worked with Prescott Bush, brother of President Bush, to establish a
golf course in Shanghai, the source said.
   Jiang made an impressive showing last month when he played host
to Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev during Gorbachev's visit to
the city. The two talked about economic reforms.
   ``He has a combination of suaveness but also a history of
managing difficult situations that undoubtedly recommended him for
this job,'' said Lynn White, an instructor at Princeton University
and visiting scholar at the University of Hong Kong, who spent the
second half of 1988 in Shanghai.
   White said Jiang lost some popularity among Shanghai citizens for
``representing Beijing at least as well as he represented them,''
and for his recent moves against the World Economic Herald, China's
most liberal newspaper before it was shut down in May.
   Jiang moved swiftly to arrest protesters and quell demonstrations
that broke out in Shanghai after the military crackdown in Beijing
on June 3-4. The first Chinese condemned for participating in the
protest movement were three Shanghai men who were executed Wednesday.
   The Chinese source said Jiang was supported by his two relatively
liberal predecessors, Zhao and the late Hu Yaobang, and has always
had a good relationship with intellectuals.
   His ties with Zhao and intellectuals were strained, however,
after Jiang moved to censor the World Economic Herald and its editor
Qin Benli, the source said.
   Jiang was born in July 1926 in Yangzhou City, near Shanghai, and
joined the Communist Party in 1946.
   A year later he graduated from the Electrical Machinery
Department of Jiaotong University in Shanghai.
   He worked as a trainee at an automobile factory in the Soviet
Union in 1955, then returned to China the next year to become deputy
chief engineer for dynamic mechanics at a plant in northeastern
China and deputy director of the Shanghai Electrical Equipment
Research Institute.
   Jiang, like most bureaucrats of his generation, apparently was
purged from office during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. He
reappeared in 1980 as a senior official in the State Administration
Commission on Import and Export Affairs and the State Administration
Commission on Foreign Investment.
   He went on to be named minister of electronics industry and in
1985 returned to Shanghai as mayor and deputy secretary of the party
committee.
   In 1986, during student demonstrations in Shanghai, he went to
his alma mater and, seeing a poster with Chinese-language excerpts
from Lincoln's Gettysburg Address, surprised students by reciting in
English from the speech.
   But he also told students they only knew the words and not the
essence of the American president's speech, and later criticized
students for their ``superficial'' knowledge of the West.
   The source in Hong Kong said Jiang has limited understanding of
Russian. According to official profiles, he reads Romanian, French
and Japanese, and is fond of music and literature.
   He is said to be the son-in-law of Li Xiannian, China's former
president and one of the Old Guard hard-liners who have supported
senior leader Deng Xiaoping in the suppression of dissent.
</TEXT>
