<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     06-24 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Raid University Campus, Arrest Student Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot troopers backed by fire trucks
raided a university campus before dawn Saturday and arrested 21
students accused of organizing violent anti-government protests,
police said.
   Police said about 3,500 riot police searched two buildings at
Hanyang University in eastern Seoul for student leaders.
   At least 21 students were arrested, but many more escaped before
police arrived, police said. Police said hundreds of firebombs and
clubs were seized.
   Radical students, a powerful minority on campuses, have used the
Hanyang campus as a stronghold of anti-government protests.
   Also Saturday, in the southern provincial capital of Kwangju,
news reports said about 400 radical students armed with firebombs
and steel bars attacked prosecutors' offices, burning two cars and
injuring five policemen.
   The attackers briefly occupied the compound of a three-story
building housing prosecutors' offices and fled after shattering
windows of the building and 16 cars, the reports said.
   Police arrested three students. One student was seriously injured
when he jumped off the top of the building, shouting slogans
denouncing the government, said Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.
   Police have raided university campuses in recent weeks to arrest
radical students leaders. About 500 dissidents and radicals have
been arrested and sent to jail so far this year.
   The dissidents are demanding the fall of the government of
President Roh Tae-woo and the withdrawal of the 43,000 U.S. troops
in South Korea. They say the American presence hampers
reconciliation with communist North Korea.
</TEXT>
