<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-24 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At age 81 she may have thought she had
seen everything, but Dale Granzeau ran into something new when she
encountered a squirrel swimming in her toilet.
   The animal apparently ended a fall down a plumbing vent Friday by
swimming through a waste pipe and bobbing up in the toilet bowl
about the same time Mrs. Granzeau was stirring from a night's sleep.
   ``I screamed and ran out and shut the door,'' she said. ``I had
hysterics. I'm still shaking about it.''
   When all other explanations for finding a squirrel in the toilet
were exhausted, police concluded the animal fell into the roof vent
pipe, said Sgt. James Kubath.
   ``Sometimes I don't even open my eyes when I get up in the
morning. Can you imagine finding this?'' asked Eileen Butler, a
manager at Bruesewitz, a local plumbing contractor where workers
said they had heard of such mishaps before.
   Marvin McCray said he'd never seen anything like it. The 22-year
veteran of the Racine County Humane Society was called to net the
3-month-old squirrel, which he released outside.
   ``I don't think he'll be trying that again,'' McCray said.
   McCray said he's seen just about every animal come down a
fireplace, including ducks, hawks, raccoons and squirrels, but an
animal swimming up the toilet was a new one for him.
   Mrs. Granzeau said she already had contacted a plumber to put a
screen over the vent pipe.
   ``I hope I never see this again,'' she said. ``What a bad start
for the day.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a dolphin appeared in Manhattan's East
River, the locals, understandably, got concerned.
   ``I think it's going to die,'' fretted Vincent Perez, 15, as he
stared down into the murky waters. ``The only thing you see in here
is garbage ... cars and shopping carts.''
   The shoreline at East 96th Street was filled Friday with police,
journalists and concerned citizens, all peering off-shore.
   ``I called 911,'' said John Soto, 41, who lives nearby. ``I'd
hate to see a dolphin get killed by these speedboats and Circle Line
boats.''
   Those who know say the dolphin seemed to be doing just fine.
   One expert said the visitor can easily dodge boats as long as its
sonar is working. And Louis Garibaldi, director of the New York
Aquarium, figures the dolphin is contentedly feasting on marine
munchies such as black bass and herring, which also (yes, it's true)
live in the waterway.
   Garibaldi said a staff member came to the area Wednesday when the
dolphin was first reported sighted.
   ``It looks like it's most likely a whitesided dolphin,'' he said.
``It appears in good health and has no trouble swimming.''
   His staff advised police and others to leave the dolphin alone,
and he noted that harassment of a marine mammal is against federal
law.
   A woman who answered the phone at the aquarium Saturday said that
officials there are monitoring the dolphin, but she wasn't sure if
they had seen it Saturday.
</TEXT>
