<SECOND>AM-Surprise Protest,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Singer Surprises Authorities with Television Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia's leading rock star
apparently caught officials of a song contest off guard by calling
for more civil rights in his country in a live television broadcast.
   ``This nation is at a crossroads ... we are more than ever
responsible for what happens now, we must work hard but also demand
the restoration of civil rights and freedoms,'' singer Michael Kocab
said during an impromptu interview Friday night after being
presented with an award in the city of Decin, 80 miles north of
Prague.
   ``I'd like to remind everyone of an old Czech saying that `every
nation gets the government it deserves,''' he added.
   Knowledgeable Czechoslovaks said it was the first time in recent
years such a statement was carried by state television.
   The brief speech drew enthusiastic applause from several thousand
spectators.
   Czechoslovakia has taken one of the hardest lines against dissent
and has been reluctant to emulate many of the political and economic
reforms introduced in the Soviet Union.
