<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   06-24 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0534,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Offers to Mediate Solution to Afghan War</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 10th graf, ``The Soviets...' to ADD first reference to
Elhih. Pickup 11th graf, `However, the...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat on Saturday
offered to mediate a political solution to the civil war in
neighboring Afghanistan, a guerrilla leader said.
   After a 30-minute meeting with Arafat at Islamabad International
Airport, guerrilla leader Gulbadin Hekmatyar said the provisional
government established by the insurgents will vote on Arafat's offer.
   Hekmatyar is foreign minister of the government, which the
U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas plan to install in Afghanistan if they
oust the Marxist government.
   Arafat later told Pakistan's National Assembly, ``I have
discussed with all the parties to this conflict our own
initiative.'' He did not elaborate.
   A spokesman for the Palestine Liberation Organization said
earlier that Arafat supported a neutral government made up of
technocrats and independent of the communists or the Moslem
insurgents.
   In the past, guerrilla leaders have rejected the neutral
government proposal.
   But the PLO representative in Pakistan, Ahmad Abdul Razzaq Al
Salman, said: ``It is very important that they change their views.''
   The guerrillas began fighting in 1978 after the communists took
over in a coup. Soviet forces entered Afghanistan a year later to
bolster the communist government and stayed for nine years.
   Moscow completed the withdrawal of its troops in February.
   ``The Soviets are gone,'' said Ahmed Abdul Karim Elhih,
Palestinian consul general in Pakistan. ``The reason to fight is
over.''
   However, the guerrillas, who have headquarters in Pakistan and
Iran, say the war will continue until they oust the Afghan
government.
   They have refused to negotiate with President Najib and his
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   In a release issued late Saturday by the guerrilla-controlled
Afghan News Agency, Hekmatyar said he told Arafat the Soviets should
stop supporting Najib and sending weapons to his forces.
   ``I also told him that the mujahedeen do not accept the idea of
sharing power with Najib,'' Hekmatyar said.
   But Elhih said the insurgents should relent. ``Why not talk to
your enemies? If you have courage to fight, you should have courage
to talk,'' he said.
   He said both sides had approached Arafat about mediating and that
the PLO leader met earlier with representatives of Najib and the
guerrillas.
   Arafat, who was welcomed at the airport by Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto, previously visited Pakistan in March. Then, he laid the
cornerstone for a Palestinian Embassy and met with guerrilla leaders.
   Guerrilla sources said at the time that the meeting accomplished
little. Arafat urged the insurgents to push for a political solution
to the war instead of a military one.
   The guerrillas rejected the idea.
   During this Pakistani visit, Arafat also discussed the
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, telling the National Assembly it will end only after Israeli
troops withdraw.
   He called on the United States to press for an international
peace conference, with the PLO as a full partner in negotiations.
Israel has rejected such a proposal.
   Ms. Bhutto said following Arafat's speech, ``It is clearly not
the Palestinian people who want to see the conflict continue, but it
is those who do not believe in freedom and peace, who have used arms
to terrorize.''
   A PLO official said Ms. Bhutto made a ``personal'' donation of
$50,000 to the uprising in April.
</TEXT>
