<FIRST>r a AM-ExxonValdez     06-24 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Instruments Show No Stress As Crippled Vessel Moves Into Open Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The damaged tanker Exxon Valdez was towed
Saturday through the often stormy Gulf of Alaska, but there was no
sign of stress at critical points and no significant dribbling of
residual oil near the ship.
   The 897-foot tanker ran aground three months ago on Bligh Reef,
ripping large gashes in its hull and releasing nearly 11 million
gallons of heavy North Slope crude oil into Prince William Sound,
causing the nation's worst oil spill.
   The vessel was refloated two weeks after the accident and towed
25 miles to an already soiled anchorage near Naked Island. There,
divers and salvage crews made it seaworthy for the 2,500-mile trip
to a San Diego shipyard where it is scheduled for $25 million in
repairs. Two ocean-going tugs began towing the huge tanker out of
Alaska waters early Friday.
   The procession was halted about four hours Friday night for a
final Coast Guard inspection before leaving the Hinchinbrook
Entrance and proceeding into open water, officials said.
   ``The strain gauges aboard the vessel showed no stress,'' Joe
Tucker, an Exxon spokesman in Valdez, said Saturday. ``There was no
trace of oil on or near the boat.''
   Observers who earlier had watched the procession lift anchor
under gray and gloomy skies reported a light film of oil trailing
the virtually empty tanker. But the Coast Guard released a statement
prepared by Exxon that generally discounted the seriousness of those
observations.
   A light sheen was observed coming off the Exxon Valdez ``for a
few minutes after the ship's departure,'' said Coast Guard
spokeswoman Brenda Toledo, who quoted from the statement.
   It was believed that most of that sheen was a ``bio-mass,''
microorganisms or algae, ``plus an insignificant'' amount of oil
that washed out of the open tanks during turbulence as the vessel
got under way, the statement said.
   The sheen was very thin _ too thin for skimmer boats to pick up,
officials said. Some of it was recovered by absorbant pads,
officials said.
   ``The Coast Guard has said this was not considered serious and
not unexpected,'' Toledo read.
   ``All discharge has stopped,'' she said. ``There has been none
since the initial startup.''
   The vessels have been moving at about 6 knots and were to slow to
an average speed of 5 knots as they continue toward Southern
California, officials said.
</TEXT>
