<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill-Scene     06-24 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Scene,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cleanup Spectators Express Anger, Resignation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people lined the shore on
Saturday, clutching binoculars to see if their fears of an
environmental disaster in Rhode Island Sound had been realized.
   What they saw _ a wounded oil tanker barely a mile offshore,
listing and ringed with Coast Guard boats _ left many with feelings
of resignation or anger.
   Diane Collins sat on a lonely rock outcrop, alternately staring
at the World Prodigy, which leaked more than 1 million gallons of
heating fuel when it struck a reef Friday, and scanning the water,
hoping not to see any of the fuel washing ashore.
   ``I'm pretty devastated myself, because if something hurts the
earth, it hurts me, too. I worried about the Alaska one, too, but
this is right on our doorstep,'' she said.
   At a nearby state park, spectators were lined along the road by 5
a.m., watching the process of unloading the tanker's remaining oil.
   ``If the oil comes in on our beaches, there goes the beaches,''
said Joanne Burns.
   Her husband, Bryan, who said he could remember three or four
tankers running aground during the past 50 years, was resigned to
it, ``as long as you're going to have an economy.''
   ``But that's a little close,'' his wife said, pointing to the
ship.
   Word that the Greek captain had failed to pick up a harbor pilot
before navigating the treacherous entrance to Narragansett Bay
sparked some anger.
   ``Guys like that ought to hang. I have no mercy for people like
that,'' said Steve Ellis of Newport.
   The ship was not inland far enough to require a pilot, but some
officials said it was unwise of the captain to operate without one.
   ``It's kind of a gray area out there,'' said Chief Warrant
Officer Jerry Alfred, a Coast Guard marine safety investigator.
   ``When the Valdez happened, I said to myself it's a wonder it
doesn't happen around here with all the traffic that comes up and
down the bay,'' Ellis said. ``But it's probably going to happen
again some day with this coastline the way it is and the amount of
traffic. ...
   ``I think they learned a lot from the Valdez that it's not wise
to sit around and wait for the company to clean it up.''
   ``The water is literally orange in some places where the waves
are breaking,'' said Chip Young, a spokesman for the environmental
group Save the Bay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
