<DOCNO> AP890624-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-OilSpill-Tourism     06-24 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Tourism,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Spill, Tourists Crowd Newport Mansions, Restaurants</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major offshore oil spill forced beaches
to close but failed to keep determined tourists away from Newport's
famous mansions, restaurants, and even its oil-besmirched harbor on
Saturday.
   While officials were busy trying to reduce the potential of an
oil spill of up to 1.5 million gallons, visitors shopped, went out
in tour boats and waited in line at restaurants.
   ``It's like it never happened,'' said Walter Andrews, manager of
the Newport Marriott.
   ``The people are just walking around shopping, they have their
maps, they have their brochures. It's a typical day,'' said Robert
Rosenberg, executive director of the Newport County Convention and
Visitors' Bureau.
   As many as 20,000 sunbathers were left stranded when the state
closed beaches in Newport and nearby Narragansett, but the dedicated
found other amusements to pass the time.
   Despite a request by the state Department of Environmental
Management that boaters stay off the water, the Salem Pro Sail
Series continued as scheduled with only a slight delay.
   Stephen G. Morin, chief of the DEM's emergency response team, had
said ``We don't want boats churning up the oil slick.''
Nevertheless, harbor tours continued to run.
   ``Today seems to be a business as usual day,'' said Rosenberg.
   ``A lot of people don't even know (the spill) is around here,''
he said. ``They're on vacation, either they've been out all morning
and haven't listened to the news, haven't picked up a paper, or
maybe they aren't as concerned about this as we would like to think
they are.''
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete said he thought the effects of the spill
on tourism would be temporary.
   ``By and large it should not affect tourism,'' he said.
   The Marriott and the Sheraton Islander, both located in downtown
Newport, were fully booked, manangers said.
   A noxious smell that had permeated the area late Friday had
lessened, they said. Lance LaFleur, night manager at the Newport
Marriott, said the odor had been so foul it woke him up Friday
evening.
   At the Inn at Castle Hill at Brenton Point, the site where the
World Prodigy struck a rock Friday afternoon, visitors were lined up
to get into the dining room, said a reservation agent who would not
give her name.
   ``Our dining room is booked full to capacity. We are turning
people away,'' she said, adding that such heavy business was normal
this time of year. The slick was not visible from the dining room,
she said.
   On Friday, some Newporters had expressed concern the five-mile
slick would impact on the Ocean State's lucrative tourist industry.
   Tourists spent about $1.1 billion in Rhode Island in 1987, a 15
percent increase over 1986, according to the University of Rhode
Island. In Newport, tourism is the largest industry.
   ``No one's going to want to come down here,'' said Brett
Wagenbach, 18, a waitress at the Black Pearl, a popular oceanfront
restaurant in Newport. ``I think it's going to affect the whole
summer, depending on how big it is.'' She said business was slower
than usual Friday night.
   But Rosenberg said visitors were just choosing other options. A
group of scuba divers were a little disturbed they couldn't go, but
then cheered up when they decided to tour the mansions instead.
   The coastal road near the spill and Bellevue Avenue, the seaside
street dotted with castle-like mansions, were rerouted to one-way
traffic, but Rosenberg said it was flowing without problem.
   The traffic was changed in an attempt to deter curious onlookers,
who had caused traffic jams Friday as they drove by the spill, said
Newport Police Officer Michael McKenna.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
