<SECOND>AM-BRF--Blasphemous Footwear, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0507,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sacrilegious Shoes Spark Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with new protests Saturday, riot police
guarding Beta shops; No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Moslem demonstrators
carrying placards and shouting slogans marched through the capital
Saturday in a second day of protest against slippers that reputedly
blaspheme Islam, police said.
   The government banned the sale of the slippers and seized unsold
stocks on Friday, the same day angry Moslems attacked shops owned by
the manufacturer, the Canadian-based Beta Shoe Co.
   Some Moslems consider the rubber slippers offensive to Islam
because they bear a logo resembling the Arabic characters for Allah.
   Clashes with police Friday in Dhaka and Mymensigh, a town 70
miles to the north, left at least 30 people injured, police said on
condition of anonymity.
   On Saturday, riot police guarded the 10 shops owned by Beta and
about 2,000 protesters called for a worldwide boycott of the
Canadian company. Riot police were stationed at strategic points of
the city but no clashes were reported.
   Islam is the state religion of Bangladesh, and 90 percent of the
country's 110 million people are Moslem.
