<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSTests     06-24 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Tests,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Legislature Votes To Repeal Premarital AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's only law requiring AIDS
testing for a marriage license needs only Gov. James R. Thompson's
signature to be off the books.
   The Legislature sent a repeal measure to Thompson's desk on a
33-23 Senate vote late Friday.
   A spokesman for Thompson said the governor had not decided
whether to sign the bill, which was approved in the House last month
on a 65-48 vote.
   Sen. William Marovitz, the bill's sponsor, said that Louisiana,
the only other state to have adopted such a law, already had
repealed its statute. He also noted that such groups as the Illinois
State Medical Society were opposed to the testing requirement.
   ``This is a low-risk population,'' Marovitz said, referring to
couples applying for marriage licenses.
   The state Department of Public Health said that through mid-June,
44 people had tested positive for exposure to the AIDS-causing virus
out of an estimated 221,000 marriage-license applicants who have
been tested since the requirement started in January 1988.
   ``This is not good public health policy,'' Marovitz said. ``The
key to this disease is education, getting people to come in
voluntarily and be tested.''
   ``There's nothing in the law, should we pass this bill, that will
bar someone from having an AIDS test,'' he said.
   Critics countered that the premarital tests help monitor the
spread of acquired immune deficiency syndrome and reduce the chance
of children getting the disease even though those testing positive
for the AIDS virus can still marry.
   ``That child is an innocent and we have a right to protect the
children,'' said Sen. Adeline Geo-Karis.
   ``You eliminate the testing program, you eliminate public
awareness,'' said Sen. Jack Schaffer. ``I think we ought to keep the
test going. Frankly, I hope it never shows up a lot of positives.''
   The measure would also repeal the requirement that couples be
tested for syphilis before getting married.
   A study by public health officials estimated that the cost that
engaged couples had to pay for testing and associated doctors'
visits was about $2.5 million over six months last year, or $312,000
for each of the eight cases of infection identified during that
period.
   The authors of the study also noted that the state was losing
thousands of dollars in revenue becauses Illinois couples were
traveling to neighboring states to get married to avoid paying for
the AIDS tests.
</TEXT>
