<FIRST>r w AM-StallingsThreat     06-24 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stallings Threat,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Priest Says He's Forbidden to Say Mass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE RUMSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black Washington priest who announced plans
to form a separate black Catholic church said Saturday he has been
forbidden to celebrate Mass or other church rites.
   Rev. George Stallings said he also was fired from his job as
Washington archdiocesan evangelist. Stallings said the notice was
contained in letters from Cardinal James Hickey of the District of
Columbia Archdiocese.
   Stallings said Hickey told him, ``I must urge you in the
strongest possible terms to turn away from this fatal course.''
   Stallings said he expected harsh criticism from Hickey and other
church officials, because the move represents a schism with the
organized Roman Catholic diocese. Stallings said Hickey's letters
labeled the move ``a significant step toward separating yourself
from the Catholic Church.''
   Stallings has not received any communication directly from the
Vatican, said an associate who asked not to be identified. Stallings
said, however, he was surprised by the wording of Hickey's letters.
   ``This is strong language,'' he said. ``It is not the language of
a man who claims to be the personal representative of the Pope...
and the representative of Christ.''
   Charging the church with ignoring the ``spiritual and cultural
needs'' of black parishioners, Stallings last week announced plans
to form a new black congregation.
   Stallings said Saturday he still plans to hold the first services
of the new church July 2. ``We will consider it a Catholic
service,'' he said.
   Stallings also said he plans to hire a bodyguard although he has
received no specific threat. ``I have no other choice but to think
my life is in jeopardy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
