<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WorstSpills-US     06-24 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Worst Spills-US,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of 10 of the worst oil spills in U.S. history
according to Golob's Oil Pollution Bulletin, which has kept records
since 1976.
   1. March 24, 1989, tanker Exxon Valdez, Prince William Sound,
Alaska, 10.92 million gallons of crude spilled when ship ran aground.
   2. Nov. 1, 1979, tanker Burmah Agate, in Galveston Bay, Texas, up
to 10.7 million gallons of oil burned or spilled when two ships
collided.
   3. Dec. 15, 1976, tanker Argo Merchant, off Massachusetts'
southeast Atlantic coast, 7.6 million gallons of crude spilled when
ship ran aground.
   4. Nov. 6, 1985, exploratory well near Ranger, Texas, 6.3 million
gallons of oil spilled onto ground after a blow-out.
   5. Jan. 2, 1988, Ashland Oil Co. above-ground storage tank,
Jefferson Borough, Pa., 3.8 million gallons of oil spilled when tank
ruptured, some going into the Monongahela River.
   6. July 30, 1984, tanker Alvenus, off Cameron, La., 2.8 million
gallons of oil spilled after ship ran aground in the Gulf of Mexico.
   7. Oct. 31, 1984, the tanker Puerto Rican, 2 million gallons of
oil spilled when a ship caught fire following an explosion in the
Pacific Ocean outside the Golden Gate, San Francisco.
   8. Aug. 18, 1984, Triangle Oil Corp., above-ground storage tank,
Jacksonville, Fla., 2.5 million gallons of oil burned after
lightning sparked a fire.
   9. Nov. 22, 1980, the tanker Georgia, 1.3 million gallons of oil
spilled after an anchor chain caused ship to leak off Pilottown, La.
   10. March 31, 1982, tanker Arkas, 1.47 million gallons of oil
burned and spilled after a ship collision and fire at Montz, La.
</TEXT>
