<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-24 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summer Showers Drench Much of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the nation was soggy Saturday as a tropical depression
hovering off Texas brought heavy rain _ Houston got 5 inches _ and
an area of New York got 2{ inches in 45 minutes.
   A cluster of showers and thunderstorms over the northwestern Gulf
of Mexico turned into a tropical depression Saturday. Its center was
off the lower coast of Texas, and it showed little movement.
   Heavy rain drenched the coastal areas of Texas and southwestern
Louisiana. In Texas, up to 5 inches of rain soaked the Houston area,
and, to the south, Matagorda received more than 4 inches of rain
with some street flooding reported.
   A flood watch and a flash flood watch were in effect for the
coastal areas of Texas. A coastal flood watch was in effect for the
middle and upper coast of Texas.
   Flood warnings were issued early Saturday for counties in
northwest and northeast New Jersey as small streams rose out of
their banks.
   Elsewhere, a warm front in the central Plains and an upper level
weather disturbance crossing the Dakotas combined to produce showers
and thunderstorms in the central United States, from Kansas to South
Dakota.
   A stationary front brought showers and thunderstorms in the
northeastern part of the nation, scattering showers from New York to
the middle Atlantic Coast on Saturday afternoon.
   In New York, thunderstorms around Binghamton produced 2{ inches
of rain in 45 minutes, and wind gusted to 67 mph at Syracuse. Flood
warnings were posted Saturday for three western New York waterways.
   Showers and thunderstorms were numerous across the Florida
peninsula.
   The rest of the United States, however, enjoyed fair to partly
cloudy skies.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 50
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 96 degrees at
Phoenix, Tucson, and Yuma, Ariz.
   Sunday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
through much of the southeast quarter of the nation; numerous
showers and thunderstorms across the Florida peninsula and over
south central and eastern Texas; widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms over the upper Ohio Valley, the mid Atlantic Coast
states and the lower Great Lakes region; showers and thunderstorms
also will be scattered from the northern Rocky Mountain region to
the upper Mississippi Valley, with showers and thunderstorms most
numerous from northeastern Montana to the upper Mississippi Valley;
and fair to partly cloudy throughout the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were forecast above 90 degrees across the southern
tier of nation, above 100 degrees in the southwestern deserts; 90
degrees in northern California and southwestern Oregon; in the 70s
from the northern and central Rockies to upper Michigan and across
New England; and in the 80s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
