<FIRST>u a AM-TexasSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0531 06-24 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Collision Spills Oil from Barge in Houston Ship Channel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to CORRECT that barge sted tug collided
with cargo vessel, UPDATE with barge emptied and removed, ship channel
reopened, quote on outlook for cleanup. Picks up 11th graf, `Kennedy said....'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PORTE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coast Guard and cleanup crews battled
strong wind and rough water Saturday to survey and try to contain a
250,000-gallon oil spill from a barge ruptured in a collision in the
Houston Ship Channel.
   The winds of more than 15 mph with higher gusts prevented workers
from surrounding the barge with containment booms until late
morning, Chief Petty Officer Mark Kennedy said.
   He said the Panamanian-registered motor vessel Rachel-B collided
around 6:20 p.m. Friday with one of three barges being driven by a
tugboat owned by Coastal Towing. Investigators have not determined
who was at fault for the accident.
   The collision ruptured and emptied three of 12 tanks on one of
the barges, and each tank was holding about 2,000 barrels or 84,000
gallons of heavy crude oil, Kennedy said.
   The first major oil spill in eight years in the ship channel came
just a few hours after 1 million gallons of heating oil spilled from
a tanker off Rhode Island.
   After the remaining oil was pumped out of the damaged barge and
it was towed away Saturday, authorities reopened eight miles of the
channel they had closed from the area where it begins running inland
to Houston from upper Galveston Bay. The 40-foot-deep channel
continues through the bay southeast to Galveston, on the Gulf of
Mexico.
   The accident occurred in the bay where the ship channel
intersects with the Bayport Channel, as the tug headed inland and
the other vessel, a tanker whose cargo was not determined, headed
outbound, officials said.
   The tug operator, fearing a worse spill if the barge overturned,
maneuvered it after the accident out of the deep channel until it
was grounded in shallow water, official said.
   When the weather finally allowed a Coast Guard helicopter flight
late Saturday morning, the aerial look showed the slick stretching
two miles to the Galveston Bay shoreline between Red Bluff and the
Bayport Channel, Kennedy said. It was nearly continuous and about a
mile wide at its widest point, he said.
   The barge owner hired a contractor, Garner Environmental, to
contain and clean up the spill, Kennedy said. Workers laid booms
around the barge and also to direct the flow of the spill away from
shore and into the Bayport Channel.
   ``It looks pretty good at this point. If we can get it contained
within Bayport Channel, it should be fairly easy to clean up,''
Kennedy said. ``Some of the slick is already being driven into that
area by the winds and rains, so they're just trying to funnel it all
in.''
   Kennedy said there had been no reports of damage to fish and
wildlife.
   ``Fortunately this is an area of the bay where there are not many
environmentally sensitive areas,'' he said, adding that the flow of
the spill apparently did not endanger shrimp grounds or oyster beds
in the bay.
   The last major spill in Galveston Bay occurred in 1981 when the
Olympic Gloria dumped about 7,000 barrels of oil after a collision
with a tanker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
