<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-PaulSimon     06-24 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Paul Simon,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paul Simon, African Musicians Play in Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exiled musicians from South Africa, a Zulu choir
and Paul Simon brought thousands of Soviets to their feet for two
hours Saturday as Simon's ``Graceland'' tour opened in Moscow.
   Some 5,000 people, including many foreigners, gathered on a warm
evening in Gorky Park for the concert. The musicians included the
10-man Zulu choir, Ladysmith Black Mambazo, and South African exiles
Miriam Makeba, a singer, and Hugh Masekela, a trumpeter.
   It was the first Soviet appearance by the 47-year-old Simon, and
the official Tass news agency indicated it was the first time black
South African musicians have performed in Moscow. The Soviet Union
and South Africa do not have diplomatic relations.
   For the $9 admission price, spectators were treated to the
hymn-like a cappella harmonies of the Zulu choir, Masekela's ballad
about trains bringing blacks to work in South African mines, and
songs by Simon, who sang works ranging from ``Graceland'' to ``The
Sound of Silence.''
   By Western standards Soviet audiences are usually sedate, but
when Simon took the stage hundreds of spectators crowded before him
to dance and sing. Thousands more stood on benches, clapping and
tapping their feet to the beat.
   The tour is based on Simon's Grammy Award-winning record
``Graceland,'' a fusion of American pop and black South African
music. A second concert was scheduled Sunday in Gorky Park before
the tour leaves for West Germany.
   The tour began in Brussels on June 15.
   Before Simon arrived in Moscow, Tass quoted him as saying, ``the
place I was most curious to play was Russia.
   ``Now, with the political tensions relaxing, I know from the
point of view of Americans that there's just a great feeling of
relief and interest in Russians and Russian culture,'' Simon was
quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
