<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e AM-JazzFestival     06-24 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jazz Festival,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snoopy Meets Jazz At New York Jazz Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wynton Marsalis woke his band up early Saturday,
even though they had played a late show the night before to help
kick off this year's JVC Jazz Festival.
   Marsalis had an important piece of business to take care of
Saturday afternoon. He was passing on the tradition.
   In a delightful program called ``Cooling It With Snoopy,''
Marsalis used his trumpet to entertain a theater full of children,
giving both the kids and their parents plenty to enjoy.
   Marsalis has won wide acclaim for his jazz recordings and
performances. He has carved out a second career as a classical
artist. All the time he has maintained yet another career, less
celebrated but perhaps likely to have as much or more impact as his
performances.
   That's Wynton Marsalis the teacher. He devotes much of his time
to clinics for student musicians at all levels.
   Saturday he looked out at an audience whose members were mostly
too young to have begun music lessons. His job was to give them the
bug _ get them interested.
   Snoopy paraded down the center aisle of New York's Town Hall
theater as Marsalis, members of his regular group and a few friends
played the familiar theme from the Peanuts television specials.
   Then Marsalis explained to Snoopy how a jazz band was put
together. The bass walks. ``The drums in a jazz band are like the
motor in a car,'' he said. ``It gives it the energy, the drive.''
   The saxophone, trumpet, trombone and clarinet can be mournful,
happy, wild and restrained, Marsalis explained _ and the musicians
demonstrated.
   Marsalis had the audience counting the four beats in a jazz
shuffle, the three beats of a waltz and the 12 measures in the blues.
   One of the highlights was the performance of 13-year-old Amani
A.W. Murray on alto sax and 12-year-old Jason Marsalis, Wynton's
brother, on drums. ``I want you to hear how kids play jazz,'' Wynton
said. In the case of these two, kids play jazz amazingly well.
   Judging by the audience's reaction to Marsalis, Snoopy and host
Murray Horwitz, director of cultural affairs programming at National
Public Radio, the concert was a whopping success.
</TEXT>
