<FIRST>r a AM-TropicalWeather     06-24 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Depression Forms Off Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The season's second tropical depression formed off
Texas and could hit parts of the Gulf Coast with 10 inches of rain,
the National Hurricane Center reported Saturday.
   Winds reached 35 mph around the poorly defined center of the
system southeast of Corpus Christi, and were expected to push tides
3 feet above normal along the Texas and Louisiana shores.
   Rainfall in excess of 10 inches is possible in that area, said
forecaster Miles Lawrence.
   The system was drifting slowly northward and little change is
indicated, he said.
   The tropical depression would be upgraded to the season's first
storm and named Allison if sustained winds reach 39 mph. The 1989
Atlantic hurricane season began June 1 and ends Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
