<SECOND>AM-Britain-Riot,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-Wing, Minority Groups Rally; Youths Go On Rampage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEWSBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock-throwing youths battled with police
Saturday after rallies by a minority workers' group and the
right-wing British National Party. Two officers were injured and 79
demonstrators were arrested, authorities said.
   Police, anticipating clashes between the groups, deployed more
than 700 officers and the government banned marches that were to
have followed the rallies that drew a total of about 400 people.
   Police ringed the rally sites of the National Party and a local
organization of workers from the Indian and Pakistani community in
this city 180 miles northwest of London. Mounted officers, dog
handlers and riot squads carrying shields and wearing helmets stood
by.
   The clashes occurred after the rallies when police moved in to
clear the town center of demonstrators. A police statement reported
no fights between the groups but that youths broke windows and
severely vandalized a pub.
   Police estimated 250 people attended the workers' rally. The
British National Party supporters, estimated by police at 150, held
a half-hour meeting and most left town in buses. The National Party
is a small, white neo-Nazi organization.
   A police spokesman said that after the rallies, groups of young
people in the town center threw rocks and other objects at police.
Officers carrying shields were sent into the area.
   Youths set off a smoke bomb and attempted to barricade one road,
police said. Nineteen cases of vandalism were reported, they said.
