<HEAD>Eleven Wounded During General Strike, Prisoner Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new 3d graf bgng: Israeli authorities... to ADD report
on freed American. Pickup 3rd graf `The army...'; ADDS 4 grafs more details
on American.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers raided villages in the occupied
West Bank on Saturday to arrest suspected participants in the
Palestinian uprising and wounded at least six Arabs, according to
the army and Arab reports.
   They also said a Palestinian suspected of collaborating with
Israel was killed at a detention center in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   Israeli authorities said a U.S. relief worker, kidnapped in the
Gaza Strip and released Friday after being held for 30 hours,
apparently cooperated with his Palestinian captors. Israeli radio
described the victim, Chris George, 35, as ``hostile toward Israel''
and Israeli television said security authorities were considering
taking unspecified measure against him.
   The army said ``many suspects'' were arrested in the raids on
several West Bank villages.
   Arab reporters said that four women ages 19 to 46 were shot and
wounded in the arms and legs during a raid on the village of Jaba.
   They said women rushed to the streets and protested when soldiers
ordered males ages 12 to 45 to the village school's courtyard.
Troops then beat some of the men, the reporters said.
   An army spokesman said soldiers encountered ``a violent
resistance by Jaba residents'' and wounded three Palestinians in
clashes.
   The army command confirmed a total of six wounded in the raids.
Arab hospital officials said at least seven were wounded.
   At the Ketziot detention center in the Gaza Strip, a 23-year-old
Palestinian carried the body of Mohammed Faraj Abu Jadalla out of a
tent, threw it in front of a guard and said he strangled Jadalla
because the man collaborated with Israeli authorities, the news
agency Itim said.
   Palestinian reporters said the 22-year-old detainee was beaten
and strangled.
   At least 65 suspected collaborators are among the 531
Palestinians killed in the 18{-month uprising against Israeli rule
of the occupied lands. Twenty-three Israelis also have died.
   Palestinians in the territories heeded calls from the Moslem
fundamentalist Hamas movement and staged a general strike on
Saturday to protest the desecration of the Holy Koran by Israeli
soldiers.
   A soldier recently used pages of a Koran as toilet paper. He
later said he could not read Arabic and apologized publicly.
   In scattered clashes in Gaza, soldiers shot and wounded at least
four Palestinians, Arab hospital officials reported. The army said
it was checking the reports.
   George, co-director of the Save the Children Foundation, was
kidnapped Thursday by three men. After his release, he said his
abduction was ``not only immoral but also a criminal act.''
   A senior Israeli security official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said, ``It is clear that George did not stage the
kidnapping itself, but he apparently cooperated with the abductors
from the moment he was taken.''
   Israel television's Arabic-language broadcast said security
authorities were considering taking measures against George but it
did not elaborate.
   George was not available for comment Saturday.
</TEXT>
