<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru   06-24 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0579,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Says Will Shoot Down Drug-Smuggling Private Planes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to CORRECT that tribunal to consider case
of Ochoa only. Pickup 11th graf `U.S. prosecutors...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military announced Saturday it will shoot
down private planes violating Cuban air space on grounds they
probably are engaged in drug smuggling.
   An armed forces announcement also said a military honor tribunal
was scheduled to convene Sunday in the case of Division Gen. Arnaldo
Ochoa Sanchez, a decorated combat veteran accused of having links
with a Colombian cocaine cartel.
   Both announcements were published in Granma, the official
newspaper of the ruling Communist Party.
   Earlier this week Granma published a lengthy report of a drug
scandal that led to the arrests of Ochoa, a brigadier general, two
colonels, a lieutenant colonel, a captain and a major.
   The report on aircraft said Cuba has been hospitable to Caribbean
air traffic but it now must act to stop drug-smuggling planes from
using its airspace.
   ``Private aircraft often violate Cuban airspace and refuse to
land despite repeated warnings,'' the statement said. ``Such
irregular flights ... can only be explained as drug trafficking
activity.
   ``We will be obliged to shoot, however disagreeable it might be,
at whatever aircraft ... refuses to obey orders to land for
inspection,'' it added.
   U.S. Federal Aviation Administraton officials in Miami said Cuba
has been granting overflight permission almost automatically to
commercial and private planes. It also has allowed unauthorized
flights to pass through its airspace for a variety of reasons,
including weather and emergencies.
   Ochoa will go before a 47-member military tribunal, accused of
disgracing the nation by allegedly collaborating with Colombia's
Medellin cartel in smuggling cocaine to the United States.
   He was arrested June 12. Cuba reported after his arrest that 10
other military officers and government officials were accused of
accepting bribes from drug traffickers.
   U.S. prosecutors have said the names of some of the officers
became known during an investigation in Miami of a Cuban smuggling
ring that led to two indictments and a trial in Florida in 1988.
   ``It is clear that these arrests (of the Cuban officers) are
substantially connected to information generated at this trial,''
U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen told The Associated Press in Miami.
   He did not identify the other officers. The Miami Herald said the
Bush administration may ask Cuba for permission to interview Ochoa.
   Ochoa and the other defendants are accused of letting smugglers
use military airports and of escorting drug-laden boats through
Cuban waters.
   U.S. authorities said an undercover agent in the 1987
investigation flew into Cuba's Varadero air base escorted by Cuban
MiGs and used Cuban military frequencies.
   Granma acknowledged on Thursday that President Fidel Castro
ordered the investigation that led to Ochoa's arrest after the U.S.
charges that Cuba was being used as a transshipment point for
cocaine.
   The scandal, the first public admission that Cuba has been
touched by the drug trade, created an uproar in Havana. People
mobbed news vendors Saturday buying copies of Granma before they
could even reach the newsstands.
   Ochoa, 57, is a veteran of the Cuban revolution and was a field
commander in Angola in 1987 and 1988. He is one of only five
officers to receive the medal of the Hero of the Republic of Cuba.
   Granma, in its report Saturday, portrayed him as a man obsessed
with money and said, ``A true revolution will never permit impunity.
We shall wash in an exemplary manner outrages like this one.''
   Granma did not say if the military tribunal would meet in public
session, but an official of the Foreign Ministry said ``it must be
in a large place, because of the great interest this has generated.''
   The newspaper said among the members of the honor tribunal are
four division generals, 31 brigadier generals, a vice admiral and a
rear admiral.
   The tribunal, to be headed by Division Gen. Ulises Rosales de
Toro, will make recommendations regarding Ochoa to the Communist
Party and the government, Granma said.
   One of the Miami cases involved Hugo Ceballos, a Venezuelan
convicted on a 10-count indictment last year that accused him of
bringing cocaine through Cuba to the Florida Keys.
   In March, Reinaldo Ruiz and three others pleaded guilty to a
related 27-count indictment and are awaiting sentencing. Ruiz
allegedly headed a Caribbean-based smuggling ring that involved
Cuban military officials.
   The only Cuban official publicly named in the Ruiz case was
``Fidel'' _ a possible reference to Castro _ who Ruiz, on a secretly
recorded videotape, claimed was pocketing bribes from smugglers
using Cuban territory.
   ``The money went right in Fidel's drawer,'' Ruiz boasted to an
undercover agent on the tape. He also said he landed at military
airports and had drug-smuggling boats escorted through Cuban waters
by military torpedo boats.
</TEXT>
