<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Slaying     06-24 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Slaying,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Police Intelligence Chiefs Arrested In Scandal Over Slain Reporter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two commanders in the intelligence division of
the capital's police department were arrested Saturday on charges
they took part in the 1984 slaying of investigative reporter Manuel
Buendia.
   Officers Juventio Prado Hurtado and Raul Perez Carmona are being
held at the Northern Penitentiary, officials reported.
   A source at the Mexico City police department said three agents
in the intelligence division also were arrested. The source,
speaking on condition of anonymity, did not elaborate.
   The police department announced it will restructure the
scandal-tainted intelligence division. Critics compare it to the
Federal Security Administration that was disbanded in 1985 because
of corruption.
   Jose Antonio Zorrilla Perez, director of the Federal Security
Administration at the time it was closed, has been indicted on
charges of being the mastermind of the the killing of Buendia on May
30, 1984.
   Francisco Villa, a spokesman for the Mexico City police
department, said Prado and Carmona were subdirectors in the
disbanded federal agency, which was similar to the FBI. Villa said
they are now commanders in the intelligence division.
   Several members of the Federal District Assembly, or city
council, have accused the intelligence division of human rights
violations and said it also should be disbanded.
   Villa said the division will be restructured but details have not
been worked out.
   Zorrilla, 47, is accused of having Buendia slain, allegedly
because of fear the columnist would report links to prominent drug
traffickers.
   Buendia, in his column in the newspaper Excelsior and in books,
exposed wrongdoing in high places and wrote about other politically
sensitive subjects.
   His murder galvanized the Mexican press and it has pressed two
successive federal administrations to solve the case. A year ago the
Mexico City district attorney publicly mentioned Zorrilla as a
suspect.
   On the fifth anniversary of Buendia's death the news media again
raised questions about the investigation and Zorrilla, a former
congressman.
   Shortly afterward, Zorrilla was arrested and charged with murder.
</TEXT>
