<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Gasoline     06-24 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Gasoline,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Raises Fuel Prices for Third Time Since December</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities raised gasoline and diesel-fuel
prices Sunday by at least 40 percent, the latest in a series of
sharp price increases.
   The official PAP news agency said the increases are needed to
help control the demand for automotive fuel. Long lines have formed
outside many service stations in recent weeks and some stations have
closed early because of a lack of gasoline.
   Price increases, listed according to the equivalent in U.S.
gallons and dollars are: High-octane gasoline raised from $1.13 per
gallon to $1.58. Low octane from 90 cents to $1.35. Diesel fuel from
59 cents to $1.04.
   The average monthly income in Poland is about $117.
   It was the third increase in gasoline prices since Jan. 1. Prices
for sugar and washing machines were raised last week.
   Inflation in 1989 is running at an annual rate of more than 100
percent.
</TEXT>
