<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HistoricAuction 1stLd-Writethru a0601 06-24 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Historic Auction, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historic Estate of Declaration Signer Auctioned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `The New Hampshire ...' to CORRECT book was
not written by Bartlett; picks up 12th graf, `There also ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two pieces of 18th century furniture
brought $180,000 on Saturday as descendants auctioned the estate of
Declaration of Independence signer Josiah Bartlett.
   ``Oh, my gosh!'' exclaimed Ruth Ready, Bartlett's
great-great-great-great granddaughter, as a representative of the
state made the winning bid of $100,000 for a maple highboy. ``I
didn't think they were going to bid for that.''
   Massachusetts antique dealer Wayne Pratt of Marlborough won an
apothecary chest used by Bartlett, founder of the New Hampshire
Medical Society, for $80,000. Bartlett's handwritten labels are
still on the drawers.
   ``It was probably the best example of that kind of thing I've
ever seen in my life,'' said Pratt, who runs antique stores in
Marlborough and on Nantucket. ``It's a fantastic piece of
furniture.''
   D. Byers, an associate of auctioneer Martin Willis, received some
bids by telephone. Willis said the $100,000 bid for the highboy, a
tall chest of drawers, was the most ever paid for such a piece.
   Winning bidders also had to pay an extra 10 percent of their bids
for the auctioneer's commission.
   The extensive collection of letters, papers, clothing and
furniture was auctioned under huge tents in a field adjacent to the
1774 Bartlett homestead. About 500 people attended.
   In addition to signing the Declaration, Bartlett served as
president of New Hampshire and later as its governor, as well as a
judge.
   He signed the Articles of Confederation, by which the nation was
governed before the Constitution, and played a role in New
Hampshire's decisive ratification of the U.S. Constitution in June
1788.
   Bartlett's papers included a 1743 copy book from his school days
in Amesbury, Mass., where he was born in 1729; official
correspondence; a 1748 receipt for payments to the families of two
soldiers and an Indian killed near Concord, N.H., during the French
and Indian War; Bartlett's charter for the New Hampshire Medical
Society; and a copy of a handwritten biography of Josiah Bartlett by
his son Levi.
   The New Hampshire Historical Society spent an estimated $55,000
at the auction, paying $13,500 for a printed version of the original
charter of the New Hamsphsire Medical Society.
   There also was a 1765 agreement, believed to be one of the first
of its kind in the colonies, making Dr. Amos Gale an apprentice in
Bartlett's medical practice.
   Only a handful of the estates of the signers of the Declaration
of Independence remain with their descendants, according to state
archivist Frank Mevers.
   Ready, 38, owns the home with her aunt, Janet Donahue of New
Rochelle, N.Y., who wanted to settle the rest of the estate.
   Ready said they had a choice between dividing everything and
selling it item by item or having an auction. She hopes to buy her
aunt's half of the house with her proceeds from the auction.
   Donahue, 71, said she regretted parting with family heirlooms,
but felt she needed to because of financial reasons. But she was
pleased to see some of the articles stay in the public domain.
   ``I would like to see the whole country get to know Josiah and
what he did,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
