<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-OwlSummit     06-24 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Owl Summit,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit Fails To Reach Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists and timber industry
officials were unable to reach an agreement Saturday over the
conflicting needs of loggers and spotted owls.
   Members of Oregon's congressional delegation and Gov. Neil
Goldschmidt spent the day questioning representatives from both
sides. Environmentalists and loggers are battling over the future of
Oregon's old growth forests, where the dwindling population of
Northern spotted owls nest.
   Meanwhile, at the state Capitol a few blocks away, hundreds of
loggers, millworkers and their families rallied in support of the
timber industry.
   Many wore yellow ribbons, symbolizing their view that the
industry is being held hostage by environmental lawsuits over the
spotted owl.
   ``As far as they're concerned, if we turned the whole damned
state into a park that would be dandy,'' said state Rep. Peg Jolin,
whose husband works in sawmill.
   Estimated to number fewer than 6,000 in the Northwest, the owl
hunts and nests almost exclusively in the old growth forests that
produce the logs most prized by the timber industry. Proposals are
being considered that would designate the spotted owl a threatened
species.
   At the owl summit, the timber industry found an ally in
Goldschmidt when he called for legislation to prohibit legal
challenges in court once the administrative process was exhausted
over national forest planning.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., opposed the idea, saying the massive
Exxon Valdez oil spill might have been averted if environmental
groups hadn't been barred from court challenges over the Alaska oil
pipeline.
   Sen. Mark Hatfield, chairman of the meeting, was unable to get
the two sides to agree about how much old growth is remaining. The
timber industry maintains there are 7.5 million acres of old growth
in Oregon and Washington; the Wilderness Society says it is more
like 2.1 million acres.
   ``Is there any way we can get these groups together to stipulate
with some kind of consistency?'' Hatfield asked.
   During the meeting, Larry Tuttle, Oregon director of the
Wilderness Society, agreed to closely examine millions of acres of
timberlands that lie between the old growth estimates in an effort
to help free up some timber for immediate use.
   Goldschmidt challenged whether environmentalists were truly
willing to compromise.
   ``Is it really possible for you folks to engage in a serious
discussion of timber supply?'' Goldschmidt asked. ``You keep taking
away from the base.''
   The meeting was called by Goldschmidt, Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore.,
and Hatfield, R-Ore. The wood products industry is the biggest
single industry in Oregon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
