<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-GayMarch     06-24 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Gay March,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March in Support of Gay Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people marched through London Saturday
in support of homosexual rights.
   Scotland Yard police headquarters said an estimated 13,000 people
participated in the peaceful march led by members of the Lesbian and
Gay Pride organization.
   The procession began in Hyde Park, passed through Parliament
Square, crossed Westminster Bridge and ended with a rally in
Kennington Park.
   Actor Ian McKellen addressed the crowd and urged more homosexual
men and women to make public their sexuality by ``coming out.''
   ``Why are there not more actors who are out in this country, more
teachers, more lawyers, more members of the royal family?'' he asked.
   Labor Party legislator Chris Smith also spoke at the rally and he
said he wanted to see a society where everyone was ``proud and open
about their sexuality and what they do.''
   In New York City about 600 people marched from Greenwich Village
to Central Park for a rally marking Lesbian and Gay Pride Weekend.
Organizers expected more than 200,000 people for a parade Sunday
down New York's Fifth Avenue in the main event of the weekend.
   The events wind up a month of activities commemorating the 20th
anniversary of the Stonewall Rebellion on June 27, 1969, when
homosexual patrons fought back during a police raid on the Stonewall
Inn in Greenwich Village.
</TEXT>
