<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     06-24 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Political Group Holds First Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Yugoslavia's first
independent political group called for democratic reform at a
congress in the liberal republic of Slovenia Saturday, the state
news agency Tanjug said.
   Addressing some 200 delegates of the Slovenian Democratic Union,
leader Dimitrij Rupel said the group will strive to compete with the
League of Communists, the only legal party in Yugoslavia since World
War II.
   In January, Rupel said at his organization's constituent assembly
in Ljubljana that the group will work toward parliamentary
democracy, free elections and the free exchange of ideas.
   Representatives of the Slovenian Socialist Alliance, a
communist-run umbrella organization, and the Slovenian Communist
Party, also addressed the congress, the union's first, Tanjug said.
   Yugoslavia, a loose federation of six republics and two provinces
containing various nationalities and religions is passing through
its worst economic and political crisis. Annual inflation exceeds
600 percent, Europe's highest, unemployment is widespread and there
has been an alarming increase in social and ethnic tension.
   Northern Slovenia is the nation's most developed and most liberal
republic. The republic's communist leadership advocates regional
autonomy, closer ties with the West and has indicated an openness to
democratic elections.
   The Democratic Union is the first of several political
associations that have been formally constituted in Slovenia.
   Slovenian liberalism has been viewed with misgivings by communist
leaders in the country's other republics, particualarly in Serbia,
Yugoslavia's government center. There, orthodox communists oppose
reforms as a step toward restoration of the Western-style democracy
that Yugoslavia had before the war, favoring greater central control
and a stronger federal government.
   The clash between the two republics, characterized by official
media as a propaganda campaign between two countries at war, has
generated Serbian and Slovenian nationalist feelings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
