<FIRST>u i AM-GanderCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0593 06-24 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gander Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0593,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Pilots Assn. Says Canadian Crash Probe Inaccurate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, ``A majority...'' to remove extraneous word;
Pickup 10 pvs, ``In his...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Air Line Pilots Association says Canadian
investigators relied on fabricated and erroneous evidence when they
probed the 1985 Gander crash that killed 256 Americans.
   The charge is contained in a letter sent this week to the
Canadian Aviation Safety Board, which investigated the crash of the
Arrow Air DC-8 carrying U.S. troops home for Christmas from a
peacekeeping mission in the Middle East.
   Canadian investigators used a computer simulation to reconstruct
the plane's flight path, which gave crucial support to the
investigators' theory that wing ice caused the aircraft to stall and
crash after takeoff on Dec. 12, 1985.
   But Harold Marthinsen, director of accident investigation for the
U.S. association said in the nine-page letter that he suspected the
simulator used manufactured data.
   ``It should be clear they simply conjured up their trajectory
with faulty, or perhaps more to the point, fabricated data,''
Marthinsen said. ``This (simulation) ... represents technical
dishonesty at its highest.''
   In Washington, officials of the pilot's association were
unavailable for comment Saturday.
   The letter comes at a critical point in the saga of the worst
aviation disaster in Canada.
   The Canadian federal government is to receive a report within the
next week from an independent investigator, former Supreme Court
justice Willard Estey. Appointed in March, Estey will appraise the
probe and suggest whether a judicial inquiry is warranted.
   A majority of five Canadian investigating board members concurred
with a final report issued in December, but four dissenters said the
plane did not stall and concluded an on-board explosion was probably
at fault.
   In his letter, Marthinsen wrote: ``We have over 20 years of
experience reading out hundreds of metal foil flight recorder
tapes.''
   In all these years, we have not seen such abuse of data as in
this investigation,'' the letter said. ``The flight recorder was put
in airplanes as a tool to assist accident investigators to arrive at
the true causes of accidents. They were not intended to allow
conjecture which suddenly changes to factual conclusions.''
   The crash killed all eight crewmembers and 248 U.S. military
personnel on their way to Ft. Campbell, Ky.
</TEXT>
