<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     06-24 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Defends Expropriations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega Saturday
defended the expropriation of three major sugar production
facilities, saying they planned to halt production.
   The expropriations have been sharply criticized by the private
sector.
   The Superior Council of Private Business has accused the leftist
Sandinista government of forcing Nicaragua into ``total
radicalization'' and the Nicaraguan Union of Agricultural Producers
formally broke ties with all government-sanctioned unions and
government agencies.
   The government seized the sugar concerns Wednesday, saying they
had adopted ``irresponsible attitudes in the face of the economic
crisis confronting the country.''
   Ortega Saturday accused the business council and the sugar
concerns of planning to halt production and said they were
``agents'' of ``the terrorist policies of the United States
government.''
   On June 22, the government also took over three coffee
plantations owned by its critics. Ortega accused the growers of
trying to sabotage an economic austerity plan to reduce inflation,
which last year topped 20,000 percent.
   As part of the plan, the Sandinista government earlier this week
ordered a 110 percent devaluation of the cordoba currency, which
sent prices of consumer goods and services skyrocketing.
   At a meeting Sunday in Matagalpa, 80 miles north of the capital,
coffee growers unanimously decided to withdraw from the National
Coffee Commission. They said the panel, made up of government and
private representatives, had ruined the industry.
   Coffee, like sugar, is one of Nicaragua's main export items and a
principal dollar-earner.
   In June 1988, the Sandinista government confiscated the San
Antonio sugar plantation and mills, one of Nicaragua's largest
industries.
</TEXT>
