<FIRST>u a AM-DelawareSpill 3rdLd-Writethru a0590 06-24 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Delaware Spill, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0590,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Tanker Runs Aground On Delaware River</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 21 grafs to reflect that river not source of drinking
water for Wilmington; UPDATE with oil beginning to surface, globs washing
ashore, quotes from interior secretary and head of EPA; edits to conform
and ADDS byline; picks up 13th graf pvs, `Although the...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLAYMONT, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil tanker from Uruguay ran aground
early Saturday, spilling as much as 1.6 million gallons of heavy
industrial heating oil in the Delaware River just south of here, the
Coast Guard said.
   ``The ship has told us 1.6 million (gallons),'' said Todd Nelson,
a Coast Guard spokesman. ``We are going to go with that because we
want to be ready to respond to a worst-case scenario.''
   Nelson said there is no way to know exactly how much has spilled
because ``a significant'' amount of oil may have sunk. The ship was
carrying 28 million gallons.
   Earlier the Coast Guard had estimated between 100,000 and 200,000
gallons of refined No. 6 industrial heating oil had leaked from the
Presidente Rivera.
   Claymont is just upriver from Wilmington, the most populated city
in Delaware. Wilmington does not get its drinking water from the
Delaware River.
   Blobs of oil roughly 1 feet to 10 feet in diameter were beginning
to surface Saturday night as far as 6 miles upriver and 7 miles
downriver from the spill, Nelson said.
   The first priority was to unload the ship's cargo so that it
could be floated back into the river's channel with the high tide
Sunday morning, Nelson said. Workers could not unload the ship fast
enough to meet the 7 p.m. high tide Saturday.
   After floating the ship, workers can then concentrate on the
clean-up, he said.
   ``The oil is not particularly toxic and we were told by our
environmental people to be at least as mindful of doing physical
damage to the marshes when placing the booms as being worried about
any long-term damage from the oil,'' said Capt. Larry Murdock, who
supervised the cleanup.
   Containment booms were placed along creeks, tributaries and bird
sanctuaries around the spill. Murdock said officials started with
marshes on the New Jersey side of the river because they thought the
tide would take the oil in that direction.
   The oil was already collecting on the Delaware side of the
shoreline, Nelson predicted it could pose a serious threat to birds.
   ``We're afraid it's just a matter of time'' until birds are
affected, Nelson said.
   Murdock said the cause of the accident was under investigation.
Coast Guard officials had not determined whether the leak had
stopped.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan got an aerial tour of the spill
and said it didn't appear as extensive as he had been told. But the
head of the Environmental Protection Agency, William Reilly, also
toured the site and said the reason it didn't look so bad was likely
because most of the oil had sunk.
   ``It's maddening and it's frustrating,'' said Andrew Altman, who
was among about 100 people who gathered to look at the dirty water.
``America is drunk on oil and the government is asleep at the
wheel.''
   The grounding at 4:45 a.m. ripped open two tanks that contained a
total of 5 million gallons on the bottom of the ship, Murdock said.
   The remaining oil in the two tanks was being transferred to a
barge alongside the vessel.
   Murdock said the ship was carrying 28 million gallons to Sun Co.
at Marcus Hook, Pa., south of Philadelphia. Claymont, Del., is just
south of the Pennsylvania-Delaware border, and across the river from
New Jersey.
   Although the ship was headed upstream, Murdock said it was
pointed downstream after the accident. The bow turned after running
aground, leaving the entire ship wedged on a sandbar.
   Coast Guard Lt. Jim Weakley said the captain of the ship is Raul
de Barrat. Weakly said a local river pilot was on board, but he had
no information on who was piloting the ship at the time of the
accident.
   Weakley said Sun Oil hired a pollution cleanup contractor about
5:40 a.m., and that a Coast Guard pollution investigative team
arrived at 6:30 a.m. The Coast Guard boat arrived at 6:50 a.m.
   ``It is a typical response time,'' Weakley said.
   Murdock said any crew members subject to the investigation would
be investigated for drug or alcohol use.
</TEXT>
