<DOCNO> AP890624-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StockbridgeAnniversary     06-24 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stockbridge Anniversary,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norman Rockwell's Village Celebrates Its 250th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents who served as models for
Norman Rockwell's paintings of small-town life paraded down Main
Street on floats and in convertibles Saturday to celebrate
Stockbridge's 250th anniversary.
   In the background were the familiar backdrops from Rockwell's
Saturday Evening Post covers _the Red Lion Inn, the pharmacy, the
town hall and the fire station.
   In one convertible was former Police Chief William Obanhein, the
``Officer Obie'' made famous by Arlo Guthrie's ballad ``Alice's
Restaurant'' and the movie based on it.
   Next to the chief was Dr. Donald E. Campbell, the general
practitioner who made housecalls for more than 30 years before
retiring this year. Rockwell immortalized him as he patiently held a
hypodermic needle while a bare-bottomed boy checked the medical
degrees hung on his office wall.
   Police said 5,000 to 7,000 people jammed the town for the
festivities, roughly tripling its year-round population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
