<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SubmarineRaces     06-24 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Submarine Races,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organizers Shorten Human-Powered Sub Races</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor visibility and rough currents on
Saturday forced organizers of the first human-powered submarine
races to scrub much of the day's events.
   Race spokeswoman Deb Cronin said the original 1-kilometer loop
course was abandoned after most of the 18 submarines had difficulty
maneuvering their crafts underwater. She also said judges and timers
had problems locating the subs in the rough seas off Riviera Beach,
about 40 miles north of Fort Lauderdale.
   ``We're keeping in mind that no one's ever done this before,''
said Liz Kay, spokeswoman for the Highham, Mass.-based H.A. Perry
Foundation, which organized the event along with Florida Atlantic
University of Boca Raton.
   On Saturday, nine submarines completed the straight 100-yard
course.
   The submarine from California Polytechnic State University in San
Luis Obispo, Calif., beat the sub from the U.S. Naval Academy in
Annapolis, Md., by about eight seconds. Applied Physics Laboratory
of the University of Washington came in third. The California
Polytechnic's sub finished the 100-yard course in 1:16.16.
   Organizers planned more races for Sunday.
   All the subs are ``wet'' designs that fill up with water and
require racers to wear scuba gear. Those propelling the subs say the
biggest challenge is to maintain a steady pace and not breathe too
quickly, which could lead to light-headedness or blackouts due to
oxygen deficiency.
   The awards ceremony is scheduled for Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
