<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Boy'sDeath     06-24 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boy's Death,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Who Touched Hearts Of Ex-President, Police Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AZUSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chuckie Haney was never prouder than when he
was wearing the police uniform officers had made for him. Next week,
the 14-year-old who suffered from a rare brain disease will be
buried in it.
   ``He'd put that uniform on and he'd just think there was nobody
better,'' his mother, Susan Haney, said Friday. ``Being a cop gave
him the chance, in his mind, to be able to help people. That's when
he was at his proudest.''
   Chuckie, whose gallant fight for life won the hearts of former
President Reagan, actor Michael Landon and scores of others, died
Friday at his suburban Los Angeles home.
   ``He had such spirit and courage,'' said Capt. Joe Santoro of the
Monterey Park Police Department, which had the uniform made. ``He
was really and truly a fighter. Everybody here admired him for
that.''
   The youth suffered from adrenoleukodystrophy, an incurable
illness that attacks the brain and nervous system. He had lapsed
into a coma last month.
   Near the bed where he spent his last days were an autographed
baseball from the California Angels and a football from the Chicago
Bears. The White House sent along a wooden Easter egg and police
departments from all over the country sent badges.
   Reagan, while still in office, made Chuckie an honorary member of
the Secret Service. Landon gave the boy's family $2,000.
</TEXT>
