<FIRST>r a AM-HungerStriker     06-24 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunger Striker,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Protests Conviction With Lengthy Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban immigrant protesting his
conviction on drug charges has been on a hunger strike since March 3.
   Rene Acuna, 37, of Detroit, stopped eating after a Macomb County
Circuit Court jury convicted him of conspiracy and delivery of 2
pounds of cocaine. His sentence is life in prison without parole.
   ``I've got honor. I've got dignity. I will be on a hunger strike
until I see justice in my case,'' he said in a telephone interview
from Duane L. Waters Hospital at the State Prison of Southern
Michigan at Jackson.
   Living only on water and coffee with sugar, Acuna, who once
carried 180 pounds on his 5-foot, 5-inch frame, had lost 64 pounds
by Friday.
   Acuna says he was convicted by an all-white jury solely because
he was a Hispanic in a white neighborhood of Warren when an
undercover agent bought cocaine from another Hispanic Aug. 12.
   The prosecution argued Acuna was a lookout.
   The Department of Corrections will go to court to get the
authority to force feed Acuna if his condition worsens, said Deputy
Director Leo Lalonde.
</TEXT>
