<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Greece 2ndLd-Writethru   06-24 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0610,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou's Condition Worsens; Unable to Hold Talks On New Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with wife, girlfriend visiting
hospital, details; EDITS to conform; Pickup 6th pvs, ``Papandreou's support...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caretaker Premier Andreas Papandreou,
hospitalized with pneumonia, experienced heart and kidney
complications early Sunday, hospital officials said.
   The 70-year-old socialist leader, defeated in elections last
Sunday, faces a Tuesday deadline to form a new government. He
received the mandate Friday from President Christos Sartzetakis
after conservatives, who made election gains, failed to form a
governing coalition.
   Papandreou was admitted to the cardiac section of the hospital
Thursday night for treatment of a ``respiratory infection,'' eight
months after he underwent open heart surgery in London.
   In a statement released at 2 a.m. Sunday (7 p.m. EDT Saturday),
the General State Hospital said the premier experienced heart and
kidney problems but did not elaborate. The statement said he
apparently was responding to treatment for pneumonia.
   Papandreou's ex-wife, Margaret, rushed to the hospital, where she
was joined by their four adult children. Mrs. Papandreou left after
an hour and declined to comment.
   Papandreou's 35-year-old live-in girlfriend, former airline
hostess Dimitra Liani, was also at the hospital.
   Papandreou divorced his wife of 38 years just days before the
June 18 general election in which his Panhellenic Socialist Movement
or PASOK, was defeated in its bid for a third consecutive term.
   No one party received an absolute majority in the 300-member
unicameral chamber. PASOK, with 125 seats, finished a distant second
to New Democracy, which won 145.
   President Sartzetakis had asked Papandreou to remain as caretaker
premier until a new government was formed.
   Officials at Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement or
PASOK, said no political consultations on forming a new government
were scheduled during the weekend. Papandreou had been scheduled to
confer with the head of the left-wing coalition, Harilaos Florakis,
to see whether a common ground could be found. Papandreou's support
eroded after his government was linked to a $200 million financial
scandal that forced two Cabinet ministers to step down.
   A leftist coalition, an alliance of the Greek Communist Party and
the Eurocommunists, rejected Mitsotakis' proposal to form a
temporary coalition government to bring socialist officials accused
of wrongdoing to trial before calling new elections.
   In a power-broker's position after receiving 28 parliamentary
places, leftist coalition leaders said they would also turn down
Papandreou's overtures.
   The constitution calls for mandates to be given to all three
leading parties. If they fail to receive Parliament's approval, an
attempt is made by the president to form a national unity government
composed of nonpolitical personalities acceptable to all political
parties.
   If no solution is found by July 3 when the newly elected
Parliament is scheduled to convene, then it is dissolved and a
caretaker regime takes over to lead the country to general elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
