<FIRST>r a AM--BRF-Church-Abortions     06-24 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM--BRF-Church-Abortions,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Says It'll Help Women Get Abortions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unitarian Universalists will create an
underground network to help women get safe abortions if the U.S.
Supreme Court overturns the landmark Roe vs. Wade decision, church
officials say.
   ``Let it be known here and now that if Roe versus Wade is
overturned, Unitarian Universalists will do all we can to see that
women still have access to safe abortions,'' Rev. William F. Schulz
said Friday at the Unitarian Universalist Association's annual
assembly.
   There are about 180,000 members of the association, which
includes 1,010 Unitarian and Universalist churches.
   The Supreme Court is expected to announce its decision soon in a
Missouri abortion case that could be used to overturn the Roe vs.
Wade decision that legalized abortions in 1973.
   The Missouri law at issue, passed in 1986, declares that human
life begins at conception. It restricts abortion by banning the
procedure in publicly financed hospitals and by forbidding the use
of public funds.
</TEXT>
