<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BeachSewage     06-24 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beach Sewage,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beach Closed After Broken Sewer Line Breaks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mile of Orange County coastline was
closed to swimmers after an aging pipeline ruptured and poured
900,000 gallons of raw sewage into a creek that flows into the
ocean, authorities said.
   The stretch of Aliso Beach, closed Friday, could remain off
limits to swimmers for up to a week, health officials said.
   ``Based on the magnitude of the spill, we expect at least part of
the area will remain closed until at least next Friday,'' said
Michael Wehner, chief of the Orange County Health Care Agency's
water quality program. ``This is one of the largest spills we've had
in a while.''
   The spill began when a 40-year-old sewer pipe broke late Thursday
night, said Linda Jones, assistant general manager for the South
Coast Water District.
   Health officials said bacteria in the water could make people ill
if they swim there.
   The spill was the third of the year in the area, about 50 miles
south of Los Angeles. About 100,000 gallons of raw sewage flowed
into the creek last month when stream erosion caused a sewer line to
collapse. Another 175,000 gallons poured into the creek in January
when another line broke.
</TEXT>
