<FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Rushdie     06-24 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Rushdie,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Apologizes for Misleading Readers About Rushdie Interview</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: The Mail on Sunday is cq for name of newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mail on Sunday newspaper apologized to its
readers, saying it misled them to think it published the first
interview with author Salman Rushdie since he went into hiding.
   It said it had made a serious omission last week by failing to
say the interview took place weeks before the late Iranian leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini urged Moslems to kill Rushdie for his
novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Rushdie went into hiding after Khomeini on Feb. 14 accused him of
blaspheming Islam with his novel and ordered him killed. Khomeini
died in a Tehran hospital June 3 after a lengthy illness.
   ``In publishing an interview with Salman Rushdie, we
unquestionably misled some of our readers into believing that it had
been obtained in recent weeks,'' the newspaper said in what it
called an opinion piece in its editions. ``That error _ and it was
serious _ we acknowledge and apologize for.''
   But the newspaper said it was proud of publishing the interview,
which it reported was a reprint of an interview with an American
journalist.
   It called the interview ``a compelling insight of a man on the
edge of the most hideous literary controversy of our time.''
   In printing the interview June 18, The Mail on Sunday did not say
when it had taken place but it did say it occurred ``while
journalists throughout the world have been trying to track down
Rushdie.''
   It said the interview took place in London with Ameena Meer, a
writer for U.S. and Indian literary magazines.
   Rushdie denied giving a new interview and called The Mail on
Sunday article a ``lurid and sensationalized account'' of the
earlier interview.
   Rushdie, 41, is an Indian-born Moslem who is a British citizen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
